# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: shelf-break-front
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Bathymetric maps (a more general term where navigational safety is not a concern) may also use a digital terrain model and artificial illumination techniques to illustrate the depths being portrayed.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] The global bathymetry is sometimes combined with topography data to yield a global relief model.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] **Paleobathymetry** is the study of past underwater depths.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Synonyms include **seafloor mapping**, **seabed mapping**, **seafloor imaging** and **seabed imaging**.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Bathymetric measurements are conducted with various methods, from depth sounding, sonar and lidar techniques, to buoys and satellite altimetry.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Various methods have advantages and disadvantages and the specific method used depends upon the scale of the area under study, financial means, desired measurement accuracy, and additional variables.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Despite modern computer-based research, the ocean seabed in many locations is less measured than the topography of Mars.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Seabed topography (ocean topography or marine topography) refers to the shape of the land (topography) when it interfaces with the ocean.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] These shapes are obvious along coastlines, but they occur also in significant ways underwater.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] The effectiveness of marine habitats is partially defined by these shapes, including the way they interact with and shape ocean currents, and the way sunlight diminishes when these landforms occupy increasing depths.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Tidal networks depend on the balance between sedimentary processes and hydrodynamics however, anthropogenic influences can impact the natural system more than any physical driver.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Marine topographies include coastal and oceanic landforms ranging from coastal estuaries and shorelines to continental shelves and coral reefs.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Further out in the open ocean, they include underwater and deep sea features such as ocean rises and seamounts.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] The submerged surface has mountainous features, including a globe-spanning mid-ocean ridge system, as well as undersea volcanoes, oceanic trenches, submarine canyons, oceanic plateaus and abyssal plains.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] The mass of the oceans is approximately 1.35×1018 metric tons, or about 1/4400 of the total mass of the Earth.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] The oceans cover an area of 3.618×108 km2 with a mean depth of 3,682 m, resulting in an estimated volume of 1.332×109 km3.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Originally, bathymetry involved the measurement of ocean depth through depth sounding.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Early techniques used pre-measured heavy rope or cable lowered over a ship's side.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] This technique measures the depth at one point at a time, and is therefore less efficient than other methods.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] It is also subject to movements of the ship and currents moving the line out of true, and thus is also less accurate.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] The data used to make bathymetric maps today typically comes from an echosounder (sonar) mounted beneath or over the side of a boat, "pinging" a beam of sound downward at the seafloor or from remote sensing LIDAR or LADAR systems.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] The amount of time it takes for the sound or light to travel through the water, bounce off the seafloor, and return to the sounder informs the equipment of the distance to the seafloor.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] LIDAR/LADAR surveys are usually conducted by airborne systems.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Starting in the early 1930s, single-beam sounders were used to make bathymetry maps.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Today, multibeam echosounders (MBES) are typically used, which use hundreds of very narrow adjacent beams (typically 256) arranged in a fan-like swath of typically 90 to 170 degrees across.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] The tightly packed array of narrow individual beams provides very high angular resolution and accuracy.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] In general, a wide swath, which is depth dependent, allows a boat to map more seafloor in less time than a single-beam echosounder by making fewer passes.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] The beams update many times per second (typically 0.1–50 Hz depending on water depth), allowing faster boat speed while maintaining 100% coverage of the seafloor.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Attitude sensors allow for the correction of the boat's roll and pitch on the ocean surface, and a gyrocompass provides accurate heading information to correct for vessel yaw.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] (Most modern MBES systems use an integrated motion-sensor and position system that measures yaw as well as the other dynamics and position.) A satellite-based global navigation system positions the soundings with respect to the surface of the earth.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Sound speed profiles (speed of sound in water as a function of depth) of the water column correct for refraction or "ray-bending" of the sound waves owing to non-uniform water column characteristics such as temperature, conductivity, and pressure.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] A computer system processes all the data, correcting for all of the above factors as well as for the angle of each individual beam.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] The resulting sounding measurements are then processed either manually, semi-automatically or automatically (in limited circumstances) to produce a map of the area.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Historically, selection of measurements was more common in hydrographic applications while DTM construction was used for engineering surveys, geology, flow modeling, etc.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] 2003–2005, DTMs have become more accepted in hydrographic practice.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Satellites are also used to measure bathymetry.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Satellite radar maps deep-sea topography by detecting the subtle variations in sea level caused by the gravitational pull of undersea mountains, ridges, and other masses.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] On average, sea level is higher over mountains and ridges than over abyssal plains and trenches.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] In the United States the United States Army Corps of Engineers performs or commissions most surveys of navigable inland waterways, while the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) performs the same role for ocean waterways.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Coastal bathymetry data is available from NOAA's National Geophysical Data Center (NGDC), which is now merged into National Centers for Environmental Information.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Bathymetric data is usually referenced to tidal vertical datums.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] For deep-water bathymetry, this is typically Mean Sea Level (MSL), but most data used for nautical charting is referenced to Mean Lower Low Water (MLLW) in American surveys, and Lowest Astronomical Tide (LAT) in other countries.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Many other datums are used in practice, depending on the locality and tidal regime.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Occupations or careers related to bathymetry include the study of oceans and rocks and minerals on the ocean floor, and the study of underwater earthquakes or volcanoes.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] The taking and analysis of bathymetric measurements is one of the core areas of modern hydrography, and a fundamental component in ensuring the safe transport of goods worldwide.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Another form of mapping the seafloor is through the use of satellites.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] The satellites are equipped with hyper-spectral and multi-spectral sensors which are used to provide constant streams of images of coastal areas providing a more feasible method of visualising the bottom of the seabed.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] The data-sets produced by hyper-spectral (HS) sensors tend to range between 100 and 200 spectral bands of approximately 5–10 nm bandwidths.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Hyper-spectral sensing, or imaging spectroscopy, is a combination of continuous remote imaging and spectroscopy producing a single set of data.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Two examples of this kind of sensing are AVIRIS (airborne visible/infrared imaging spectrometer) and HYPERION.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] The application of HS sensors in regards to the imaging of the seafloor is the detection and monitoring of chlorophyll, phytoplankton, salinity, water quality, dissolved organic materials, and suspended sediments.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] However, this does not provide a great visual interpretation of coastal environments.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] The other method of satellite imaging, multi-spectral (MS) imaging, tends to divide the EM spectrum into a small number of bands, unlike its partner hyper-spectral sensors which can capture a much larger number of spectral bands.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] MS sensing is used more in the mapping of the seabed due to its fewer spectral bands with relatively larger bandwidths.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] The larger bandwidths allow for a larger spectral coverage, which is crucial in the visual detection of marine features and general spectral resolution of the images acquired.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] High-density airborne laser bathymetry (ALB) is a modern, highly technical, approach to the mapping the seafloor.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] LiDAR (Light Detection and Ranging) is, according to the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, "a remote sensing method that uses light in the form of a pulsed laser to measure distances".
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] These light pulses, along with other data, generate a three-dimensional representation of whatever the light pulses reflect off, giving an accurate representation of the surface characteristics.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] A LiDAR system usually consists of a laser, scanner, and GPS receiver.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Airplanes and helicopters are the most commonly used platforms for acquiring LIDAR data over broad areas.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] One application of LiDAR is bathymetric LiDAR, which uses water-penetrating green light to also measure seafloor and riverbed elevations.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] ALB generally operates in the form of a pulse of non-visible light being emitted from a low-flying aircraft and a receiver recording two reflections from the water.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] The first of which originates from the surface of the water, and the second from the seabed.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] This method has been used in a number of studies to map segments of the seafloor of various coastal areas.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] There are various LIDAR bathymetry systems that are commercially accessible.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Two of these systems are the Scanning Hydrographic Operational Airborne Lidar Survey (SHOALS) and the Laser Airborne Depth Sounder (LADS).
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] SHOALS was first developed to help the United States Army Corps of Engineers in bathymetric surveying by a company called Optech in the 1990s.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] SHOALS is done through the transmission of a laser, of wavelength between 530 and 532 nm, from a height of approximately 200 m at speed of 60 m/s on average.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] High resolution orthoimagery (HRO) is the process of creating an image that combines the geometric qualities with the characteristics of photographs.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] The result of this process is an orthoimage, a scale image which includes corrections made for feature displacement such as building tilt.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] These corrections are made through the use of a mathematical equation, information on sensor calibration, and the application of digital elevation models.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] An orthoimage can be created through the combination of a number of photos of the same target.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] The target is photographed from a number of different angles to allow for the perception of the true elevation and tilting of the object.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] This gives the viewer an accurate perception of the target area.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] High resolution orthoimagery is currently being used in the 'terrestrial mapping program', the aim of which is to 'produce high resolution topography data from Oregon to Mexico'.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] The orthoimagery will be used to provide the photographic data for these regions.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] The earliest known depth measurements were made about 1800 BCE by Egyptians by probing with a pole.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Later a weighted line was used, with depths marked off at intervals.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Both these methods were limited by being spot depths, taken at a point, and could easily miss significant variations in the immediate vicinity.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Accuracy was also affected by water movement–current could swing the weight from the vertical and both depth and position would be affected.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] This was a laborious and time-consuming process and was strongly affected by weather and sea conditions.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] There were significant improvements with the voyage of HMS *Challenger* in the 1870s, when similar systems using wires and a winch were used for measuring much greater depths than previously possible, but this remained a one depth at a time procedure which required very low speed for accuracy.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Greater depths could be measured using weighted wires deployed and recovered by powered winches.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] The wires had less drag and were less affected by current, did not stretch as much, and were strong enough to support their own weight to considerable depths.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] The winches allowed faster deployment and recovery, necessary when the depths measured were of several kilometers.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Wire drag surveys continued to be used until the 1990s due to reliability and accuracy.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] This procedure involved towing a cable by two boats, supported by floats and weighted to keep a constant depth The wire would snag on obstacles shallower than the cable depth.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] This was very useful for finding navigational hazards which could be missed by soundings, but was limited to relatively shallow depths.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Single-beam echo sounders were used from the 1920s-1930s to measure the distance of the seafloor directly below a vessel at relatively close intervals along the line of travel.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] By running roughly parallel lines, data points could be collected at better resolution, but this method still left gaps between the data points, particularly between the lines.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] The mapping of the sea floor started by using sound waves, contoured into isobaths and early bathymetric charts of shelf topography.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] These provided the first insight into seafloor morphology, though mistakes were made due to horizontal positional accuracy and imprecise depths.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Sidescan sonar was developed in the 1950s to 1970s and could be used to create an image of the bottom, but the technology lacked the capacity for direct depth measurement across the width of the scan.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] In 1957, Marie Tharp, working with Bruce Charles Heezen, created the first three-dimensional physiographic map of the world's ocean basins.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Tharp's discovery was made at the perfect time.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] It was one of many discoveries that took place near the same time as the invention of the computer.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Computers, with their ability to compute large quantities of data, have made research much easier, include the research of the world's oceans.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] The development of multibeam systems made it possible to obtain depth information across the width of the sonar swath, to higher resolutions, and with precise position and attitude data for the transducers, made it possible to get multiple high resolution soundings from a single pass.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] The US Naval Oceanographic Office developed a classified version of multibeam technology in the 1960s.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] NOAA obtained an unclassified commercial version in the late 1970s and established protocols and standards.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Data acquired with multibeam sonar have vastly increased understanding of the seafloor.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Landsat satellites of the 1970s and later the European Sentinel satellites, have provided new ways to find bathymetric information, which can be derived from satellite images.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] These methods include making use of the different depths to which different frequencies of light penetrate the water.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] When water is clear and the seafloor is sufficiently reflective, depth can be estimated by measuring the amount of reflectance observed by a satellite and then modeling how far the light should penetrate in the known conditions.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] The Advanced Topographic Laser Altimeter System (ATLAS) on NASA's Ice, Cloud, and land Elevation Satellite 2 (ICESat-2) is a photon-counting lidar that uses the return time of laser light pulses from the Earth's surface to calculate altitude of the surface.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] ICESat-2 measurements can be combined with ship-based sonar data to fill in gaps and improve precision of maps of shallow water.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Mapping of continental shelf seafloor topography using remotely sensed data has applied a variety of methods to visualise the bottom topography.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Early methods included hachure maps, and were generally based on the cartographer's personal interpretation of limited available data.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Acoustic mapping methods developed from military sonar images produced a more vivid picture of the seafloor.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Further development of sonar based technology have allowed more detail and greater resolution, and ground penetrating techniques provide information on what lies below the bottom surface.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Remote sensing techniques have been used to develop new ways of visualizing dynamic benthic environments from general geomorphological features to biological coverage.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] A bathymetric chart is a type of isarithmic map that depicts the submerged bathymetry and physiographic features of ocean and sea bottoms.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Their primary purpose is to provide detailed depth contours of ocean topography as well as provide the size, shape and distribution of underwater features.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Topographic maps display elevation above ground (topography) and are complementary to bathymetric charts.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Bathymetric charts showcase depth using a series of lines and points at equal intervals, called depth contours or isobaths (a type of contour line).
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] A closed shape with increasingly smaller shapes inside of it can indicate an ocean trench or a seamount, or underwater mountain, depending on whether the depths increase or decrease going inward.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] Bathymetric surveys and charts are associated with the science of oceanography, particularly marine geology, and underwater engineering or other specialized purposes.
[src:shelf-break-front/bathymetry] which are vertical sections through a feature.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] In this process, a sample containing cells or particles is suspended in a fluid and injected into the flow cytometer instrument.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The sample is focused to ideally flow one cell at a time through a laser beam, where the light scattered is characteristic to the cells and their components.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Cells are often labeled with fluorescent markers so light is absorbed and then emitted in a band of wavelengths.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Tens of thousands of cells can be quickly examined and the data gathered are processed by a computer.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Flow cytometry is routinely used in basic research, clinical practice, and clinical trials.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] A flow cytometry analyzer is an instrument that provides quantifiable data from a sample.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Other instruments using flow cytometry include cell sorters which physically separate and thereby purify cells of interest based on their optical properties.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The first impedance-based flow cytometry device, using the Coulter principle, was disclosed in U.S.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Mack Fulwyler was the inventor of the forerunner to today's flow cytometers – particularly the cell sorter.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Fulwyler developed this in 1965 with his publication in *Science*.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The first fluorescence-based flow cytometry device (ICP 11) was developed in 1968 by Wolfgang Göhde from the University of Münster, filed for patent on 18 December 1968 and first commercialized in 1968/69 by German developer and manufacturer Partec through Phywe AG in Göttingen.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] At that time, absorption methods were still widely favored by other scientists over fluorescence methods.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Soon after, flow cytometry instruments were developed, including the Cytofluorograph (1971) from Bio/Physics Systems Inc.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] (later: Ortho Diagnostics), the PAS 8000 (1973) from Partec, the first FACS (fluorescence-activated cell sorting) instrument from Becton Dickinson (1974), the ICP 22 (1975) from Partec/Phywe and the Epics from Coulter (1977/78).
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The first label-free high-frequency impedance flow cytometer based on a patented microfluidic "lab-on-chip", Ampha Z30, was introduced by Amphasys (2012).
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The original name of the fluorescence-based flow cytometry technology was "pulse cytophotometry" (German: *Impulszytophotometrie*), based on the first patent application on fluorescence-based flow cytometry.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] At the 5th American Engineering Foundation Conference on Automated Cytology in Pensacola (Florida) in 1976 – eight years after the introduction of the first fluorescence-based flow cytometer (1968) – it was agreed to commonly use the name "flow cytometry", a term that quickly became popular.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Modern flow cytometers are able to analyze many thousands of particles per second, in "real time" and, if configured as cell sorters, can actively separate and isolate particles with specified optical properties at similar rates.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] A flow cytometer is similar to a microscope, except that, instead of producing an image of the cell, flow cytometry offers high-throughput, automated quantification of specified optical parameters on a cell-by-cell basis.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] To analyze solid tissues, a single-cell suspension must first be prepared.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] A flow cytometer has five main components: a flow cell, a measuring system, a detector, an amplification system, and a computer for analysis of the signals.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The flow cell has a liquid stream (sheath fluid), which carries and aligns the cells so that they pass single file through the light beam for sensing.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The detector and analog-to-digital conversion (ADC) system converts analog measurements of forward-scattered light (FSC) and side-scattered light (SSC) as well as dye-specific fluorescence signals into digital signals that can be processed by a computer.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The amplification system can be linear or logarithmic.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The process of collecting data from samples using the flow cytometer is termed "acquisition".
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Acquisition is mediated by a computer physically connected to the flow cytometer, and the software which handles the digital interface with the cytometer.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The software is capable of adjusting parameters (e.g., voltage, compensation) for the sample being tested, and also assists in displaying initial sample information while acquiring sample data to ensure that parameters are set correctly.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Early flow cytometers were, in general, experimental devices, but technological advances have enabled widespread applications for use in a variety of both clinical and research purposes.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Due to these developments, a considerable market for instrumentation, analysis software, as well as the reagents used in acquisition such as fluorescently labeled antibodies have been developed.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Modern instruments usually have multiple lasers and fluorescence detectors.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The current record for a commercial instrument is ten lasers and 30 fluorescence detectors.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Increasing the number of lasers and detectors allows for multiple antibody labeling, and can more precisely identify a target population by their phenotypic markers.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Certain instruments can even take digital images of individual cells, allowing for the analysis of fluorescent signal location within or on the surface of cells.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Cells must pass uniformly through the center of focused laser beams to accurately measure optical properties of cells in any flow cytometer.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The purpose of the fluidic system is to move the cells one by one through the lasers beam and throughout the instrument.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Fluidics in a flow cytometer with cell sorting capabilities also use the stream to carry sorted cells into collection tubes or wells.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] For precise positioning of cells in a liquid jet, hydrodynamic focusing is used in most cytometers.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The cells in suspension enter into the instrument enclosed by an outer sheath fluid.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The sample core is maintained in the center of the sheath fluid.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The sample input rate or how fast the cells flow through to the laser interrogation can be controlled by the pressure of the sheath fluid on the sample core.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Under optimal conditions, the central fluid stream and sheath fluid do not mix.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Acoustic focusing technology is used in some flow cytometers to support hydrodynamic focusing.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Acoustic waves (>2 MHz) pre-focus the sample before introduction to sheath fluid.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The pre-focused sample is then injected into the hydrodynamic core and flowed through the instrument.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] This may help with increasing data accuracy under high sample input rates.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Light emitted from fluorophores are in a spectrum of wavelengths, so combining multiple fluorophores may cause overlap.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] To add specificity, optical filters and dichroic mirrors are used to filter and move light to the detectors such as photomultiplier tubes (PMTs) or avalanche photodiodes (APD).
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Optical filters are designed as band pass (BP), long pass (LP), or short pass (SP) filters.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Most flow cytometers uses dichroic mirrors and band pass filters to select specific bands of the optical spectrum.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Spectral flow cytometry uses prisms or diffraction gratings to disperse the emitted light of a marker across a detector array.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] This allows for the full spectra from each particle to be measured.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The measured spectra from single cells are subsequently unmixed by using reference spectra of all used dyes and the autofluorescence spectrum.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] This may allow for a wider panel design and the application of new biological markers.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Imaging flow cytometry (IFC) captures multichannel images of cells.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Detectors used in imaging platforms can be equipped with charge-coupled device (CCD) or complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor (CMOS) to capture images of individual cells.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Each fluorochrome has a broad fluorescence spectrum.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] When more than one fluorochrome is used, an overlap between fluorochromes can occur.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] This situation is called spectrum overlap, and must be corrected.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] For example, the emission spectrum for FITC and PE is one in which the light emitted by the fluorescein overlaps the same wavelength as it passes through the filter used for PE.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] This spectral overlap is corrected by removing a portion of the FITC signal from the PE signals or vice versa.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] This process is called color compensation, which calculates a fluorochrome as a percentage to measure itself.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Compensation is the mathematical process by which spectral overlap of multiparameter flow cytometric data is corrected.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Since fluorochromes can have wide-ranging spectrum, they can overlap, causing the undesirable result of confusion during the analysis of data.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] This overlap, known as spillover and quantified in the spillover coefficient, is usually caused by detectors for a certain fluorochrome measuring a significant peak in wavelength from a different fluorochrome.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Linear algebra is most often used to make this correction.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] In general, when graphs of one or more parameters are displayed, it is to show that the other parameters do not contribute to the distribution shown.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Especially when using the parameters which are more than double, this problem is more severe.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Currently, no tools have been discovered to efficiently display multidimensional parameters.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Compensation is very important to see the distinction between cells.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The data generated by flow cytometers can be plotted in a single dimension to produce a histogram, or in two-dimensional dot plots, or even in three dimensions.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The regions on these plots can be sequentially separated, based on fluorescence intensity, by creating a series of subset extractions, termed "gates." Specific gating protocols exist for diagnostic and clinical purposes, especially in relation to hematology.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The plots are often made on logarithmic scales.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Because different fluorescent dyes' emission spectra overlap, signals at the detectors have to be compensated electronically as well as computationally.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Data accumulated using the flow cytometer can be analyzed using software.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Once the data is collected, there is no need to stay connected to the flow cytometer and analysis is most often performed on a separate computer.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] This is especially necessary in core facilities where usage of these machines is in high demand.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Recent progress on automated population identification using computational methods has offered an alternative to traditional gating strategies.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Automated identification systems could potentially help findings of rare and hidden populations.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Representative automated methods include FLOCK in Immunology Database and Analysis Portal (ImmPort), SamSPECTRAL and flowClust in Bioconductor, and FLAME in GenePattern.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] T-Distributed Stochastic Neighbor Embedding (tSNE) is an algorithm designed to perform dimensionality reduction, to allow visualization of complex multi-dimensional data in a two-dimensional "map".
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Fluorescence minus one (FMO) controls are important for data interpretation when building multi-color panels – in which a cell is stained with multiple fluorochromes simultaneously.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] FMO controls provide a measure of fluorescence spillover in a given channel and allow for compensation.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] To generate a FMO control, a sample is stained with all the fluorochromes except the one that is being tested – meaning if you are using 4 different fluorochromes your FMO control must contain only 3 of them (example: fluorochromes – A, B, C, D; FMOs – ABC_, AB_D, A_CD, _BCD).
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Cell sorting is a method to purify cell populations based on the presence or absence of specific physical characteristics.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] In flow cytometers with sorting capabilities, the instrument detects cells using parameters including cell size, morphology, and protein expression, and then droplet technology to sort cells and recover the subsets for post-experimental use.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The first prototype sorter was built at the Los Alamos National Laboratory (LANL) in 1965 by physicist Mack J.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Fulwyler by joining a Coulter volume sensor with the newly invented ink jet printer.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Live cell cell sorter or fluorescence-activated cell sorter (FACS) was generated by Len Herzenberg, who subsequently won the Kyoto Prize in 2006 for his seminal work.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Flow cytometry cell sorters have a collection system unlike flow cytometry analyzers.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The collection process starts when a sample is injected into a stream of sheath fluid that passes through the flow cell and laser intercepts.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The stream then carries the cell through a vibrating nozzle which generates droplets with most containing either one cell or no cells.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The charged droplets then fall through an electrostatic deflection system that diverts droplets into containers based on their charge.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] In some systems, the charge is applied directly to the stream, and the droplet breaking off retains charge of the same sign as the stream.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The stream is then returned to neutral after the droplet breaks off.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] After collecting, these cells can be further cultured, manipulated, and studied.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Flow cytometry uses the light properties scattered from cells or particles for identification or quantitative measurement of physical properties.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Labels, dyes, and stains can be used for multi-parametric analysis (understand more properties about a cell).
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Immunophenotyping is the analysis of heterogeneous populations of cells using labeled antibodies and other fluorophore containing reagents such as dyes and stains.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] A wide range of fluorophores can be used as labels in flow cytometry.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Fluorophores, or simply "fluors", are typically attached to an antibody that recognizes a target feature on or in the cell; they may also be attached to a chemical entity with affinity for the cell membrane or another cellular structure.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Each fluorophore has a characteristic peak excitation and emission wavelength, and the emission spectra often overlap.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Consequently, the combination of labels which can be used depends on the wavelength of the lamp(s) or laser(s) used to excite the fluorochromes and on the detectors available.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Flow cytometry uses fluorescence as a quantitative tool; the utmost sensitivity of flow cytometry is unmatched by other fluorescent detection platforms such as confocal microscopy.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Quantum dots are sometimes used in place of traditional fluorophores because of their narrower emission peaks.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Mass cytometry overcomes the fluorescent labeling limit by utilizing lanthanide isotopes attached to antibodies.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] This method could theoretically allow the use of 40 to 60 distinguishable labels and has been demonstrated for 30 labels.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Mass cytometry is fundamentally different from flow cytometry: cells are introduced into a plasma, ionized, and associated isotopes are quantified via time-of-flight mass spectrometry.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Although this method permits the use of a large number of labels, it currently has lower throughput capacity than flow cytometry.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] It also destroys the analysed cells, precluding their recovery by sorting.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] In addition to the ability to label and identify individual cells via fluorescent antibodies, cellular products such as cytokines, proteins, and other factors may be measured as well.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Similar to ELISA sandwich assays, cytometric bead array (CBA) assays use multiple bead populations typically differentiated by size and different levels of fluorescence intensity to distinguish multiple analytes in a single assay.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The amount of the analyte captured is detected via a biotinylated antibody against a secondary epitope of the protein, followed by a streptavidin-R-phycoerythrin treatment.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The fluorescent intensity of R-phycoerythrin on the beads is quantified on a flow cytometer equipped with a 488 nm excitation source.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Concentrations of a protein of interest in the samples can be obtained by comparing the fluorescent signals to those of a standard curve generated from a serial dilution of a known concentration of the analyte.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Commonly also referred to as cytokine bead array (CBA).
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Impedance-based single cell analysis systems are commonly known as Coulter counters.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] They represent a well-established method for counting and sizing virtually any kind of cells and particles.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The label-free technology has recently been enhanced by a "lab-on-a-chip" based approach and by applying high frequency alternating current (AC) in the radio frequency range (from 100 kHz to 30 MHz) instead of a static direct current (DC) or low frequency AC field.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] This patented technology allows a highly accurate cell analysis and provides additional information like membrane capacitance and viability.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The relatively small size and robustness allow battery powered on-site use in the field.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Measurable factors in cellular analysis and flow cytometry include a diverse set of traits and indicators that provide important insights into cell biology and function.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Flow cytometry techniques can quantify and evaluate these factors, allowing researchers to investigate and analyze various aspects of cells.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The technology has applications in a number of fields, including molecular biology, pathology, immunology, virology, plant biology and marine biology.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] It has broad application in medicine especially in transplantation, hematology, tumor immunology and chemotherapy, prenatal diagnosis, genetics and sperm sorting for sex preselection.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Flow cytometry is widely applied to detect sperm cells abnormality associated with DNA fragmentation in male fertility assays.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Also, it is extensively used in research for the detection of DNA damage, caspase cleavage and apoptosis.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Photoacoustic flow cytometry is used in the study of multi-drug-resistant bacteria (most commonly MRSA) to detect, differentiate, and quantify bacteria in the blood marked with dyed bacteriophages.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] In neuroscience, co-expression of cell surface and intracellular antigens can also be analyzed.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] In microbiology, it can be used to screen and sort transposon mutant libraries constructed with a GFP-encoding transposon (TnMHA), or to assess viability.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] In protein engineering, flow cytometry is used in conjunction with yeast display and bacterial display to identify cell surface-displayed protein variants with desired properties.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The main advantages of flow cytometry over histology and IHC is the possibility to precisely measure the quantities of antigens and the possibility to stain each cell with multiple antibodies-fluorophores, in current laboratories around 10 antibodies can be bound to each cell.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] This is much less than mass cytometer where up to 40 can be currently measured, but at a higher price and a slower pace.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] In aquatic systems, flow cytometry is used for the analysis of autofluorescing cells or cells that are fluorescently-labeled with added stains.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] This research started in 1981 when Clarice Yentsch used flow cytometry to measure the fluorescence in a red tide producing dinoflagellate.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The next year researchers published flow cytometric measurements of multiple algal species which could be distinguished based on their fluorescence characteristics.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Flow cytometry also allowed marine researchers to distinguish between dimly-fluorescing *Prochlorococcus* and heterotrophic microorganisms, a distinction that is difficult with microscopy-based assessments.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Advances in technology now allow aquatic scientists to use flow cytometers continuously during research cruises and flow cytometers are used to provide images of individual phytoplankton cells.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Cell proliferation is the major function in the immune system.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Often it is required to analyse the proliferative nature of the cells in order to make some conclusions.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] One such assay to determine the cell proliferation is the tracking dye carboxyfluorescein diacetate succinimidyl ester (CFSE).
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] It helps to monitor proliferative cells.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] This assay gives quantitative as well as qualitative data during time-series experiments.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] This dye binds covalently with the long-lived molecules present inside the cell.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] When the cells divide, the molecules divide too and, the daughter cells possess half the dye than the parent population.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] This decrease in the intensity can be visualized by flow cytometry.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] In literature, this powerful technique of flow cytometry and CFSE has been used to find the efficiency of T-cells in killing the target cells in cancer such as leukemia.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] In order to visualize the target cell death, both rapid and slow, scientists have used CFSE labelling with antibody staining of certain kinds of cells and fluorescently labelled microbeads.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] This also gave information regarding the proliferation of the target cells upon the treatment of certain cytokines.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Flow cytometry has been used to measure genome sizes, or more precisely: the amount of DNA in a cell or nucleus.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Although genomes can be analyzed with more precision by genome sequencing, this is often difficult due to a high fraction of micro-chromosomes or repetitive sequences which may be missed by sequencing (or which get filtered out during the analysis step when they cannot be assigned to chromosomes).
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] However, flow cytometry is not perfect either.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] The resulting genome sizes may differ based on the dye used.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] An analysis of fish genomes resulted in significantly different genome sizes when propidium iodide (PI) and DAPI were used, respectively.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] For instance, the genome of *Anguilla japonica* was found to contain 1.09 pg of DNA with PI vs.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] Similarly, the genome of *Myxocyprinus asiaticus* was found to contain 2.75 pg of DNA (PI) vs.
[src:shelf-break-front/flow-cytometry] That is, the differences were on the order of 12–14%.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Friction can have dramatic consequences, as illustrated by the use of friction created by rubbing pieces of wood together to start a fire.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Another important consequence of many types of friction can be wear, which may lead to performance degradation or damage to components.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] It is known that frictional energy losses account for about 20% of the total energy expenditure of the world.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] There are many different contributors to the retarding force in friction, ranging from asperity deformation to the generation of charges and changes in local structure.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] When two bodies in contact move relative to each other, due to these various contributors some mechanical energy is transformed to heat, the free energy of structural changes, and other types of dissipation.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The total dissipated energy per unit distance moved is the **retarding frictional force**, *F=E/d*.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The complexity of the interactions involved makes the calculation of friction from first principles difficult, and it is often easier to use empirical methods for analysis and the development of theory.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Many ancient authors including Aristotle, Vitruvius, and Pliny the Elder, were interested in the cause and mitigation of friction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] They were aware of differences between static and kinetic friction with Themistius stating in 350 A.D. that "it is easier to further the motion of a moving body than to move a body at rest".
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The classic laws of sliding friction were discovered by Leonardo da Vinci in 1493, a pioneer in tribology, but the laws documented in his notebooks were not published and remained unknown.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] These laws were rediscovered by Guillaume Amontons in 1699 and became known as Amonton's three laws of dry friction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Amontons presented the nature of friction in terms of surface irregularities and the force required to raise the weight pressing the surfaces together.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] This view was further elaborated by Bernard Forest de Bélidor and Leonhard Euler (1750), who derived the angle of repose of a weight on an inclined plane and first distinguished between static and kinetic friction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] John Theophilus Desaguliers (1734) first recognized the role of adhesion in friction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Microscopic forces cause surfaces to stick together; he proposed that friction was the force necessary to tear the adhering surfaces apart.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The understanding of friction was further developed by Charles-Augustin de Coulomb (1785).
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Coulomb investigated the influence of four main factors on friction: the nature of the materials in contact and their surface coatings, the extent of the surface area, the normal pressure (or load), and the length of time that the surfaces remained in contact (time of repose).
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Coulomb further considered the influence of sliding velocity, temperature and humidity, in order to decide between the different explanations on the nature of friction that had been proposed.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The distinction between static and dynamic friction is made in Coulomb's friction law (see below), although this distinction was already drawn by Johann Andreas von Segner in 1758.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The effect of the time of repose was explained by Pieter van Musschenbroek (1762) by considering the surfaces of fibrous materials, with fibers meshing together, which takes a finite time in which the friction increases.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] John Leslie (1766–1832) noted a weakness in the views of Amontons and Coulomb: If friction arises from a weight being drawn up the inclined plane of successive asperities, then why is it not balanced through descending the opposite slope?
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Leslie was equally skeptical about the role of adhesion proposed by Desaguliers, which should on the whole have the same tendency to accelerate as to retard the motion.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] In Leslie's view, friction should be seen as a time-dependent process of flattening, pressing down asperities, which creates new obstacles in what were cavities before.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] In the long course of the development of the law of conservation of energy and of the first law of thermodynamics, friction was recognised as a mode of conversion of mechanical work into heat.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] In 1798, Benjamin Thompson reported on cannon boring experiments.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Arthur Jules Morin (1833) developed the concept of sliding versus rolling friction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] In 1842, Julius Robert Mayer frictionally generated heat in paper pulp and measured the temperature rise.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Osborne Reynolds (1866) derived the equation of viscous flow.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] This completed the classic empirical model of friction (static, kinetic, and fluid) commonly used today in engineering.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Ewing investigated the continuity between static and kinetic friction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Bryan published an investigation of the foundations of thermodynamics, *Thermodynamics: an Introductory Treatise dealing mainly with First Principles and their Direct Applications*.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] He noted that for a rough body driven over a rough surface, the mechanical work done by the driver exceeds the mechanical work received by the surface.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The lost work is accounted for by heat generated by friction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Over the years, for example in his 1879 thesis, but particularly in 1926, Planck advocated regarding the generation of heat by rubbing as the most specific way to define heat, and the prime example of an irreversible thermodynamic process.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The focus of research during the 20th century has been to understand the physical mechanisms behind friction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Frank Philip Bowden and David Tabor (1950) showed that, at a microscopic level, the actual area of contact between surfaces is a very small fraction of the apparent area.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] This actual area of contact, caused by asperities increases with pressure.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The development of the atomic force microscope (ca.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] 1986) enabled scientists to study friction at the atomic scale, showing that, on that scale, dry friction is the product of the inter-surface shear stress and the contact area.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] These two discoveries explain Amonton's first law *(below)*; the macroscopic proportionality between normal force and static frictional force between dry surfaces.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Dry friction resists relative lateral motion of two solid surfaces in contact.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The two regimes of dry friction are 'static friction' ("stiction") between non-moving surfaces, and *kinetic friction* (sometimes called sliding friction or dynamic friction) between moving surfaces.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The force of friction is always exerted in a direction that opposes movement (for kinetic friction) or potential movement (for static friction) between the two surfaces.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] For example, a curling stone sliding along the ice experiences a kinetic force slowing it down.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] For an example of potential movement, the drive wheels of an accelerating car experience a frictional force pointing forward; if they did not, the wheels would spin, and the rubber would slide backwards along the pavement.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Note that it is not the direction of movement of the vehicle they oppose, it is the direction of (potential) sliding between tire and road.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Coulomb friction, named after Charles-Augustin de Coulomb, is an approximate model used to calculate the force of dry friction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The Coulomb friction $F_{\mathrm {f} }$ may take any value from zero up to $\mu F_{\mathrm {n} }$ , and the direction of the frictional force against a surface is opposite to the motion that surface would experience in the absence of friction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Thus, in the static case, the frictional force is exactly what it must be in order to prevent motion between the surfaces; it balances the net force tending to cause such motion.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] In this case, rather than providing an estimate of the actual frictional force, the Coulomb approximation provides a threshold value for this force, above which motion would commence.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] This maximum force is known as traction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Static friction is friction between two or more solid objects that are not moving relative to each other.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] For example, static friction can prevent an object from sliding down a sloped surface.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The coefficient of static friction, typically denoted as *μ*s, is usually higher than the coefficient of kinetic friction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Static friction is considered to arise as the result of surface roughness features across multiple length scales at solid surfaces.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] These features, known as asperities are present down to nano-scale dimensions and result in true solid to solid contact existing only at a limited number of points accounting for only a fraction of the apparent or nominal contact area.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The linearity between applied load and true contact area, arising from asperity deformation, gives rise to the linearity between static frictional force and normal force, found for typical Amonton–Coulomb type friction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The static friction force must be overcome by an applied force before an object can move.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The maximum possible friction force between two surfaces before sliding begins is the product of the coefficient of static friction and the normal force: $F_{\text{max}}=\mu _{\mathrm {s} }F_{\text{n}}$ .
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] When there is no sliding occurring, the friction force can have any value from zero up to $F_{\text{max}}$ .
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Any force smaller than $F_{\text{max}}$ attempting to slide one surface over the other is opposed by a frictional force of equal magnitude and opposite direction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Any force larger than $F_{\text{max}}$ overcomes the force of static friction and causes sliding to occur.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The instant sliding occurs, static friction is no longer applicable—the friction between the two surfaces is then called kinetic friction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] However, an apparent static friction can be observed even in the case when the true static friction is zero.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] An example of static friction is the force that prevents a car wheel from slipping as it rolls on the ground.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Even though the wheel is in motion, the patch of the tire in contact with the ground is stationary relative to the ground, so it is static rather than kinetic friction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Upon slipping, the wheel friction changes to kinetic friction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] An anti-lock braking system operates on the principle of allowing a locked wheel to resume rotating so that the car maintains static friction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The maximum value of static friction, when motion is impending, is sometimes referred to as **limiting friction**, although this term is not used universally.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The normal force is defined as the net force compressing two parallel surfaces together, and its direction is perpendicular to the surfaces.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] In the simple case of a mass resting on a horizontal surface, the only component of the normal force is the force due to gravity, where $N=mg\,$ .
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] In this case, conditions of equilibrium tell us that the magnitude of the friction force is *zero*, $F_{f}=0$ .
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] In fact, the friction force always satisfies $F_{f}\leq \mu N$ , with equality reached only at a critical ramp angle (given by $\tan ^{-1}\mu$ ) that is steep enough to initiate sliding.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The friction coefficient is an empirical (experimentally measured) structural property that depends only on various aspects of the contacting materials, such as surface roughness.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The coefficient of friction is not a function of mass or volume.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] For instance, a large aluminum block has the same coefficient of friction as a small aluminum block.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] However, the magnitude of the friction force itself depends on the normal force, and hence on the mass of the block.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Depending on the situation, the calculation of the normal force N might include forces other than gravity.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] If an object is on a *level surface* and subjected to an external force P tending to cause it to slide, then the normal force between the object and the surface is just $N=mg+P_{y}$ , where $mg$ is the block's weight and $P_{y}$ is the downward component of the external force.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Prior to sliding, this friction force is $F_{f}=-P_{x}$ , where $P_{x}$ is the horizontal component of the external force.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Sliding commences only after this frictional force reaches the value $F_{f}=\mu N$ .
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Until then, friction is whatever it needs to be to provide equilibrium, so it can be treated as simply a reaction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] If the object is on a *tilted surface* such as an inclined plane, the normal force from gravity is smaller than $mg$ , because less of the force of gravity is perpendicular to the face of the plane.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The normal force and the frictional force are ultimately determined using vector analysis, usually via a free body diagram.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] In general, process for solving any statics problem with friction is to treat contacting surfaces *tentatively* as immovable so that the corresponding tangential reaction force between them can be calculated.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] If this frictional reaction force satisfies $F_{f}\leq \mu N$ , then the tentative assumption was correct, and it is the actual frictional force.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Otherwise, the friction force must be set equal to $F_{f}=\mu N$ , and then the resulting force imbalance would then determine the acceleration associated with slipping.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] For certain applications, it is more useful to define static friction in terms of the maximum angle before which one of the items will begin sliding.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] This is called the *angle of friction* or *friction angle*.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] It is defined as: $\tan {\theta }=\mu _{\mathrm {s} }$ and thus: $\theta =\arctan {\mu _{\mathrm {s} }}$ where $\theta$ is the angle from horizontal and *μs* is the static coefficient of friction between the objects.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] This formula can also be used to calculate *μs* from empirical measurements of the friction angle.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The **coefficient of friction** (COF), often symbolized by the Greek letter μ, is a dimensionless scalar value which equals the ratio of the force of friction between two bodies and the force pressing them together, either during or at the onset of slipping.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The coefficient of friction depends on the materials used; for example, ice on steel has a low coefficient of friction, while rubber on pavement has a high coefficient of friction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Coefficients of friction range from near zero to greater than one.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The coefficient of friction between two surfaces of similar metals is greater than that between two surfaces of different metals; for example, brass has a higher coefficient of friction when moved against brass, but less if moved against steel or aluminum.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] For surfaces at rest relative to each other, $\mu =\mu _{\mathrm {s} }$ , where $\mu _{\mathrm {s} }$ is the *coefficient of static friction*.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] This is usually larger than its kinetic counterpart.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The fractality of surfaces, a parameter describing the scaling behavior of surface asperities, is known to play an important role in determining the magnitude of the static friction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] For surfaces in relative motion $\mu =\mu _{\mathrm {k} }$ , where $\mu _{\mathrm {k} }$ is the *coefficient of kinetic friction*.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The Coulomb friction is equal to $F_{\mathrm {f} }$ , and the frictional force on each surface is exerted in the direction opposite to its motion relative to the other surface.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Arthur Morin introduced the term and demonstrated the utility of the coefficient of friction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The coefficient of friction is an empirical measurement—it has to be measured experimentally, and cannot be found through calculations.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Rougher surfaces tend to have higher effective values.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Both static and kinetic coefficients of friction depend on the pair of surfaces in contact; for a given pair of surfaces, the coefficient of static friction is *usually* larger than that of kinetic friction; in some sets the two coefficients are equal, such as teflon-on-teflon.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Most dry materials in combination have friction coefficient values between 0.3 and 0.6.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Values outside this range are rarer, but teflon, for example, can have a coefficient as low as 0.04.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] A value of zero would mean no friction at all, an elusive property.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Rubber in contact with other surfaces can yield friction coefficients from 1 to 2.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Occasionally it is maintained that *μ* is always < 1, but this is not true.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] While in most relevant applications *μ* < 1, a value above 1 merely implies that the force required to slide an object along the surface is greater than the normal force of the surface on the object.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] For example, silicone rubber or acrylic rubber-coated surfaces have a coefficient of friction that can be substantially larger than 1.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] While it is often stated that the coefficient of friction is a "material property", it is better categorized as a "system property".
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] For example, a copper pin sliding against a thick copper plate can have a coefficient of friction that varies from 0.6 at low speeds (metal sliding against metal) to below 0.2 at high speeds when the copper surface begins to melt due to frictional heating.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The latter speed, of course, does not determine the coefficient of friction uniquely; if the pin diameter is increased so that the frictional heating is removed rapidly, the temperature drops, the pin remains solid, and the coefficient of friction rises to that of a 'low speed' test.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] In systems with significant non-uniform stress fields, because local slip occurs before the system slides, the macroscopic coefficient of static friction depends on the applied load, system size, or shape; Amontons' law is not satisfied macroscopically.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Friction is due to a range of energy dissipative processes.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The base model, first detailed by Bowden and Tabor is that it involves contact of small protusions on surfaces called asperities.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] As the load increases the number and the area of asperity contacts increases, leading to the normal force dependence of friction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] As these asperities slide past each other both plastic and elastic deformation processes take place, among others.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The frictional force is the energy dissipated per unit distance by these, the net result often being the linear Coulomb formula mentioned earlier.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Experimental studies of dry sliding friction in engineering materials have shown that friction and wear are controlled not only by the nominal contact conditions, but also by near-surface microstructural evolution, debris generation and tribochemical transformations during sliding.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Reviews and experimental studies have shown that plastic deformation, fracture, material transfer, mechanical mixing and oxidation can all contribute to the transition between mild and severe wear regimes in dry metal contacts.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The importance of debris and “third-body” material formed in the contact has also been demonstrated experimentally, since compacted triboparticulates may either accelerate damage or form protective interfacial layers that reduce direct metal-to-metal contact.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] In steels, dry sliding tests have shown that hardness level, load and sliding speed can strongly influence friction stability and wear rate, while oxidative wear may become dominant under suitable sliding conditions.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Experimental investigations further indicate that environmental factors such as hydrogen charging, lubrication regime and cyclic loading may significantly influence crack initiation mechanisms and friction stability in structural alloys.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Despite being a simplified model of friction, the Coulomb model is useful in many numerical simulation applications such as multibody systems and granular material.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Some quite nonlinear effects, such as the so-called Painlevé paradoxes, may be encountered with Coulomb friction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The Coulomb approximation is fundamentally an empirical construct.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] It is a rule-of-thumb describing the approximate outcome of an extremely complicated physical interaction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The strength of the approximation is its simplicity and versatility.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Though the relationship between normal force and frictional force is not exactly linear (and so the frictional force is not entirely independent of the contact area of the surfaces), the Coulomb approximation is an adequate representation of friction for the analysis of many physical systems.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] When the surfaces are conjoined, Coulomb friction becomes a very poor approximation (for example, adhesive tape resists sliding even when there is no normal force, or a negative normal force).
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] In this case, the frictional force may depend strongly on the area of contact.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Some drag racing tires are adhesive for this reason.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] However, despite the complexity of the fundamental physics behind friction, the relationships are accurate enough to be useful in many applications.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Dry friction can induce several types of instabilities in mechanical systems which display a stable behaviour in the absence of friction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The latter were originally discovered in 1995 by George G.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Adams and João Arménio Correia Martins for smooth surfaces and were later found in periodic rough surfaces.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] In particular, friction-related dynamical instabilities are thought to be responsible for brake squeal and the 'song' of a glass harp, phenomena which involve stick and slip, modelled as a drop of friction coefficient with velocity.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] A practically important case is the self-oscillation of the strings of bowed instruments such as the violin, cello, hurdy-gurdy, erhu, etc.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] A connection between dry friction and flutter instability in a simple mechanical system has been discovered, watch the movie Archived 2025-12-11 at the Wayback Machine for more details.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Frictional instabilities can lead to the formation of new self-organized patterns (or "secondary structures") at the sliding interface, such as in-situ formed tribofilms which are utilized for the reduction of friction and wear in so-called self-lubricating materials.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] In 2008 scientists for the first time were able to move a single atom across a surface, and measure the forces required.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Using ultrahigh vacuum and nearly zero temperature (5 K), a modified atomic force microscope was used to drag a cobalt atom, and a carbon monoxide molecule, across surfaces of copper and platinum.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] As of 2012, a single study has demonstrated the potential for an *effectively negative coefficient of friction in the low-load regime*, meaning that a decrease in normal force leads to an increase in friction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] This contradicts everyday experience in which an increase in normal force leads to an increase in friction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] This was reported in the journal *Nature* in October 2012 and involved the friction encountered by an atomic force microscope stylus when dragged across a graphene sheet in the presence of graphene-adsorbed oxygen.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The origin of kinetic friction at nanoscale can be rationalized by an energy model.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] During sliding, a new surface forms at the back of a sliding true contact, and existing surface disappears at the front of it.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Since all surfaces involve the thermodynamic surface energy, work must be spent in creating the new surface, and energy is released as heat in removing the surface.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Thus, a force is required to move the back of the contact, and frictional heat is released at the front.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Under certain conditions some materials have very low friction coefficients.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] An example is (highly ordered pyrolytic) graphite which can have a friction coefficient below 0.01.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] This ultralow-friction regime is called superlubricity.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Fluid friction occurs between fluid layers that are moving relative to each other.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] This internal resistance to flow is named *viscosity*.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] In everyday terms, the viscosity of a fluid is described as its "thickness".
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Thus, water is "thin", having a lower viscosity, while honey is "thick", having a higher viscosity.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The less viscous the fluid, the greater its ease of deformation or movement.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] All real fluids (except superfluids) offer some resistance to shearing and therefore are viscous.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] For teaching and explanatory purposes it is helpful to use the concept of an inviscid fluid or an ideal fluid which offers no resistance to shearing and so is not viscous.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Lubricated friction is a case of fluid friction where a fluid separates two solid surfaces.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Lubrication is a technique employed to reduce wear of one or both surfaces in close proximity moving relative to each another by interposing a substance called a lubricant between the surfaces.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] In most cases the applied load is carried by pressure generated within the fluid due to the frictional viscous resistance to motion of the lubricating fluid between the surfaces.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Adequate lubrication allows smooth continuous operation of equipment, with only mild wear, and without excessive stresses or seizures at bearings.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] When lubrication breaks down, metal or other components can rub destructively over each other, causing heat and possibly damage or failure.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Skin friction arises from the interaction between the fluid and the skin of an object, and is directly related to the area of the surface of the body that is in contact with the fluid.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Skin friction follows the drag equation and rises with the square of the velocity.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Skin friction is caused by viscous drag in the boundary layer around the object.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] There are two ways to decrease skin friction: the first is to shape the moving body so that smooth flow is possible, like an airfoil.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The second method is to decrease the length and cross-section of the moving object as much as is practicable.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Internal friction is the force resisting motion between the elements making up a solid material while it undergoes deformation.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The best understood case is the drag force on dislocations due to atomic vibrations (phonon drag), although electron interactions can also play a role.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] There are also contributions from dissipative forces on the motion of grain boundaries in metals, and there are similar phenomena in vitreous materials such as glasses.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] As a consequence of light pressure, Einstein in 1909 predicted the existence of "radiation friction" which would oppose the movement of matter.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] He wrote, "radiation will exert pressure on both sides of the plate.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The forces of pressure exerted on the two sides are equal if the plate is at rest.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] However, if it is in motion, more radiation will be reflected on the surface that is ahead during the motion (front surface) than on the back surface.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The backward-acting force of pressure exerted on the front surface is thus larger than the force of pressure acting on the back.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Hence, as the resultant of the two forces, there remains a force that counteracts the motion of the plate and that increases with the velocity of the plate.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Rolling resistance is the force that resists the rolling of a wheel or other circular object along a surface caused by deformations in the object or surface.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Generally the force of rolling resistance is less than that associated with kinetic friction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Typical values for the coefficient of rolling resistance for steel wheels on a track are 0.001.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] One of the most common examples of rolling resistance, with a coefficient of around 0.02, is the movement of motor vehicle tires on a road, a process which generates heat and sound as by-products.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Any wheel equipped with a brake is capable of generating a large retarding force, usually for the purpose of slowing and stopping a vehicle or piece of rotating machinery.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Braking friction differs from rolling friction because the coefficient of friction for rolling friction is small whereas the coefficient of friction for braking friction is designed to be large by choice of materials for brake pads.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Rubbing two materials against each other can lead to charge transfer, either electrons or ions.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The energy required for this contributes to the friction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] In addition, sliding can cause a build-up of electrostatic charge, which can be hazardous if flammable gases or vapours are present.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] When the static build-up discharges, explosions can be caused by ignition of the flammable mixture.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] However, as discussed recently the extent to which triboelectricity contributes to friction is contentious, with some claims that it is large, others that it is small because charge transfer can occur with superlubricious samples.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Belt friction is a physical property observed from the forces acting on a belt wrapped around a pulley, when one end is being pulled.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The resulting tension, which acts on both ends of the belt, can be modeled by the belt friction equation.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] In practice, the theoretical tension acting on the belt or rope calculated by the belt friction equation can be compared to the maximum tension the belt can support.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] This helps a designer of such a rig to know how many times the belt or rope must be wrapped around the pulley to prevent it from slipping.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Mountain climbers and sailing crews demonstrate a standard knowledge of belt friction when accomplishing basic tasks.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Devices such as wheels, ball bearings, roller bearings, and air cushion or other types of fluid bearings can change sliding friction into a much smaller type of rolling friction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Many thermoplastic materials such as nylon, HDPE and PTFE are commonly used in low friction bearings.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] They are especially useful because the coefficient of friction falls with increasing imposed load.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] For improved wear resistance, very high molecular weight grades are usually specified for heavy duty or critical bearings.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] A common way to reduce friction is by using a lubricant, such as oil, water, or grease, which is placed between the two surfaces, often dramatically lessening the coefficient of friction.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] The science of friction and lubrication is called tribology.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Lubricant technology is when lubricants are mixed with the application of science, especially to industrial or commercial objectives.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Superlubricity, a recently discovered effect, has been observed in graphite: it is the substantial decrease of friction between two sliding objects, approaching zero levels.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] A very small amount of frictional energy would still be dissipated.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Lubricants to overcome friction need not always be thin, turbulent fluids or powdery solids such as graphite and talc; acoustic lubrication actually uses sound as a lubricant.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Another way to reduce friction between two parts is to superimpose micro-scale vibration to one of the parts.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] This can be sinusoidal vibration as used in ultrasound-assisted cutting or vibration noise, known as dither.
[src:shelf-break-front/friction] Friction is an important factor in many engineering disciplines.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] In ecology, **habitat** refers to the array of resources, biotic factors that are present in an area, such as to support the survival and reproduction of a particular species.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] A species' habitat can be seen as the physical manifestation of its ecological niche.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Thus "habitat" is a species-specific term, fundamentally different from concepts such as environment or vegetation assemblages, for which the term "habitat-type" is more appropriate.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] The physical factors may include (for example): soil, moisture, range of temperature, and light intensity.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Biotic factors include the availability of food and the presence or absence of predators.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Every species has particular habitat requirements, habitat generalist species are able to thrive in a wide array of environmental conditions while habitat specialist species require a very limited set of factors to survive.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Habitat types are environmental categorizations of different environments based on the characteristics of a given geographical area, particularly vegetation and climate.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Thus habitat types do not refer to a single species but to multiple species living in the same area.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] For example, terrestrial habitat types include forest, steppe, grassland, semi-arid or desert.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Fresh-water habitat types include marshes, streams, rivers, lakes, and ponds; marine habitat types include salt marshes, the coast, the intertidal zone, estuaries, reefs, bays, the open sea, the sea bed, deep water and submarine vents.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Other changes come as a direct result of human activities, such as deforestation, the plowing of ancient grasslands, the diversion and damming of rivers, the draining of marshland and the dredging of the seabed.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] The introduction of alien species can have a devastating effect on native wildlife – through increased predation, through competition for resources or through the introduction of pests and diseases to which the indigenous species have no immunity.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] The word "habitat" has been in use since about 1755 and derives from the Latin *habitāre*, to inhabit, from *habēre*, to have or to hold.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Habitat can be defined as the natural environment of an organism, the type of place in which it is natural for it to live and grow.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] It is similar in meaning to a biotope; an area of uniform environmental conditions associated with a particular community of plants and animals.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] The chief environmental factors affecting the distribution of living organisms are temperature, humidity, climate, soil and light intensity, and the presence or absence of all the requirements that the organism needs to sustain it.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Generally speaking, animal communities are reliant on specific types of plant communities.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Some plants and animals have habitat requirements which are met in a wide range of locations.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] The small white butterfly *Pieris rapae* for example is found on all the continents of the world apart from Antarctica.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Its larvae feed on a wide range of *Brassicas* and various other plant species, and it thrives in any open location with diverse plant communities.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] The large blue butterfly *Phengaris arion* is much more specific in its requirements; it is found only in chalk grassland areas, its larvae feed on *Thymus* species, and because of complex life cycle requirements it inhabits only areas in which *Myrmica* ants live.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Disturbance is important in the creation of biodiverse habitat types.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] In the absence of disturbance, a climax vegetation cover develops that prevents the establishment of other species.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Wildflower meadows are sometimes created by conservationists but most of the flowering plants used are either annuals or biennials and disappear after a few years in the absence of patches of bare ground on which their seedlings can grow.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Lightning strikes and toppled trees in tropical forests allow species richness to be maintained as pioneering species move in to fill the gaps created.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Similarly, coastal habitat types can become dominated by kelp until the seabed is disturbed by a storm and the algae swept away, or shifting sediment exposes new areas for colonisation.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Another cause of disturbance is when an area may be overwhelmed by an invasive introduced species which is not kept under control by natural enemies in its new habitat.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Terrestrial habitat types include forests, grasslands, wetlands and deserts.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Within these broad biomes are more specific habitat types with varying climate types, temperature regimes, soils, altitudes and vegetation.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Many of these habitat types grade into each other and each one has its own typical communities of plants and animals.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] A habitat-type may suit a particular species well, but its presence or absence at any particular location depends to some extent on chance, on its dispersal abilities and its efficiency as a colonizer.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Arid habitats are those where there is little available water.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] The most extreme arid habitats are deserts.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Desert animals have a variety of adaptations to survive the dry conditions.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Some frogs live in deserts, creating moist habitat types underground and hibernating while conditions are adverse.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Other organisms cope with the drying up of their aqueous habitat in other ways.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Vernal pools are ephemeral ponds that form in the rainy season and dry up afterwards.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] They have their specially-adapted characteristic flora, mainly consisting of annuals, the seeds of which survive the drought, but also some uniquely adapted perennials.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Animals adapted to these extreme habitat types also exist; fairy shrimps can lay "winter eggs" which are resistant to desiccation, sometimes being blown about with the dust, ending up in new depressions in the ground.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] These can survive in a dormant state for as long as fifteen years.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Some killifish behave in a similar way; their eggs hatch and the juvenile fish grow with great rapidity when the conditions are right, but the whole population of fish may end up as eggs in diapause in the dried up mud that was once a pond.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Freshwater habitat types include rivers, streams, lakes, ponds, marshes and bogs.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] They can be divided into **running waters** (rivers, streams) and **standing waters** (lakes, ponds, marshes, bogs).
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Although some organisms are found across most of these habitat types, the majority have more specific requirements.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] The water velocity, its temperature and oxygen saturation are important factors, but in river systems, there are fast and slow sections, pools, bayous and backwaters which provide a range of habitat types.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Similarly, aquatic plants can be floating, semi-submerged, submerged or grow in permanently or temporarily saturated soils besides bodies of water.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Marginal plants provide important habitat for both invertebrates and vertebrates, and submerged plants provide oxygenation of the water, absorb nutrients and play a part in the reduction of pollution.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Marine habitats include brackish water, estuaries, bays, the open sea, the intertidal zone, the seabed, reefs and deep / shallow water zones.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Further variations include rock pools, sand banks, mudflats, brackish lagoons, sandy and pebbly beaches, and seagrass beds, all supporting their own flora and fauna.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] The benthic zone or seabed provides a home for both static organisms, anchored to the substrate, and for a large range of organisms crawling on or burrowing into the surface.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Some creatures float among the waves on the surface of the water, or raft on floating debris; others swim at a range of depths, including organisms in the demersal zone close to the seabed, and myriads of organisms drift with the currents and form the plankton.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Many animals and plants have taken up residence in urban environments.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] They tend to be adaptable generalists and use the town's features to make their homes.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Rats and mice have followed man around the globe, pigeons, peregrines, sparrows, swallows and house martins use the buildings for nesting, bats use roof space for roosting, foxes visit the garbage bins and squirrels, coyotes, raccoons and skunks roam the streets.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] About 2,000 coyotes are thought to live in and around Chicago.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] A survey of dwelling houses in northern European cities in the twentieth century found about 175 species of invertebrate inside them, including 53 species of beetle, 21 flies, 13 butterflies and moths, 13 mites, 9 lice, 7 bees, 5 wasps, 5 cockroaches, 5 spiders, 4 ants and a number of other groups.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] In warmer climates, termites are serious pests in the urban habitat; 183 species are known to affect buildings and 83 species cause serious structural damage.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] A microhabitat is the small-scale physical requirements of a particular organism or population.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Every habitat includes large numbers of microhabitat types with subtly different exposure to light, humidity, temperature, air movement, and other factors.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] The lichens that grow on the north face of a boulder are different from those that grow on the south face, from those on the level top, and those that grow on the ground nearby; the lichens growing in the grooves and on the raised surfaces are different from those growing on the veins of quartz.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Lurking among these miniature "forests" are the microfauna, species of invertebrate, each with its own specific habitat requirements.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] The greater the structural diversity in the wood, the greater the number of microhabitat types that will be present.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] A range of tree species with individual specimens of varying sizes and ages, and a range of features such as streams, level areas, slopes, tracks, clearings, and felled areas will provide suitable conditions for an enormous number of biodiverse plants and animals.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] For example, in Britain it has been estimated that various types of rotting wood are home to over 1700 species of invertebrate.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] For a parasitic organism, its habitat is the particular part of the outside or inside of its host on or in which it is adapted to live.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] The life cycle of some parasites involves several different host species, as well as free-living life stages, sometimes within vastly different microhabitat types.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] One such organism is the trematode (flatworm) *Microphallus turgidus*, present in brackish water marshes in the southeastern United States.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Its first intermediate host is a snail and the second, a glass shrimp.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] The final host is the waterfowl or mammal that consumes the shrimp.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Although the vast majority of life on Earth lives in mesophyllic (moderate) environments, a few organisms, most of them microbes, have managed to colonise extreme environments that are unsuitable for more complex life forms.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] There are bacteria, for example, living in Lake Whillans, half a mile below the ice of Antarctica; in the absence of sunlight, they must rely on organic material from elsewhere, perhaps decaying matter from glacier melt water or minerals from the underlying rock.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Other bacteria can be found in abundance in the Mariana Trench, the deepest place in the ocean and on Earth; marine snow drifts down from the surface layers of the sea and accumulates in this undersea valley, providing nourishment for an extensive community of bacteria.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Other microbes live in environments lacking in oxygen, and are dependent on chemical reactions other than photosynthesis.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Boreholes drilled 300 m (1,000 ft) into the rocky seabed have found microbial communities apparently based on the products of reactions between water and the constituents of rocks.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] These communities have not been studied much, but may be an important part of the global carbon cycle.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Rock in mines two miles deep also harbour microbes; these live on minute traces of hydrogen produced in slow oxidizing reactions inside the rock.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] These metabolic reactions allow life to exist in places with no oxygen or light, an environment that had previously been thought to be devoid of life.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] The intertidal zone and the photic zone in the oceans are relatively familiar habitat types.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] However the vast bulk of the ocean is inhospitable to air-breathing humans, with scuba divers limited to the upper 50 m (160 ft) or so.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] The lower limit for photosynthesis is 100 to 200 m (330 to 660 ft) and below that depth the prevailing conditions include total darkness, high pressure, little oxygen (in some places), scarce food resources and extreme cold.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] This habitat is very challenging to research, and as well as being little-studied, it is vast, with 79% of the Earth's biosphere being at depths greater than 1,000 m (3,300 ft).
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] With no plant life, the animals in this zone are either detritivores, reliant on food drifting down from surface layers, or they are predators, feeding on each other.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Some organisms are pelagic, swimming or drifting in mid-ocean, while others are benthic, living on or near the seabed.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Their growth rates and metabolisms tend to be slow, their eyes may be very large to detect what little illumination there is, or they may be blind and rely on other sensory inputs.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] A number of deep sea creatures are bioluminescent; this serves a variety of functions including predation, protection and social recognition.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] In general, the bodies of animals living at great depths are adapted to high pressure environments by having pressure-resistant biomolecules and small organic molecules present in their cells known as piezolytes, which give the proteins the flexibility they need.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] There are also unsaturated fats in their membranes which prevent them from solidifying at low temperatures.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Hydrothermal vents were first discovered in the ocean depths in 1977.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] They result from seawater becoming heated after seeping through cracks to places where hot magma is close to the seabed.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] The under-water hot springs may gush forth at temperatures of over 340 °C (640 °F) and support unique communities of organisms in their immediate vicinity.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] The basis for this teeming life is chemosynthesis, a process by which microbes convert such substances as hydrogen sulfide or ammonia into organic molecules.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] These bacteria and Archaea are the primary producers in these ecosystems and support a diverse array of life.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] About 350 species of organism, dominated by molluscs, polychaete worms and crustaceans, had been discovered around hydrothermal vents by the end of the twentieth century, most of them being new to science and endemic to these habitat types.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Besides providing locomotion opportunities for winged animals and a conduit for the dispersal of pollen grains, spores and seeds, the atmosphere can be considered to be a habitat-type in its own right.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] There are metabolically active microbes present that actively reproduce and spend their whole existence airborne, with hundreds of thousands of individual organisms estimated to be present in a cubic meter of air.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] The airborne microbial community may be as diverse as that found in soil or other terrestrial environments, however, these organisms are not evenly distributed, their densities varying spatially with altitude and environmental conditions.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Aerobiology has not been studied much, but there is evidence of nitrogen fixation in clouds, and less clear evidence of carbon cycling, both facilitated by microbial activity.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Whether from natural processes or the activities of man, landscapes and their associated habitat types change over time.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] There are the slow geomorphological changes associated with the geologic processes that cause tectonic uplift and subsidence, and the more rapid changes associated with earthquakes, landslides, storms, flooding, wildfires, coastal erosion, deforestation and changes in land use.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Then there are the changes in habitat types brought on by alterations in farming practices, tourism, pollution, fragmentation and climate change.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Loss of habitat is the single greatest threat to any species.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] If an island on which an endemic organism lives becomes uninhabitable for some reason, the species will become extinct.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Any type of habitat surrounded by a different habitat is in a similar situation to an island.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] If a forest is divided into parts by logging, with strips of cleared land separating woodland blocks, and the distances between the remaining fragments exceeds the distance an individual animal is able to travel, that species becomes especially vulnerable.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Small populations generally lack genetic diversity and may be threatened by increased predation, increased competition, disease and unexpected catastrophe.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] At the edge of each forest fragment, increased light encourages secondary growth of fast-growing species and old growth trees are more vulnerable to logging as access is improved.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] The birds that nest in their crevices, the epiphytes that hang from their branches and the invertebrates in the leaf litter are all adversely affected and biodiversity is reduced.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Habitat fragmentation can be ameliorated to some extent by the provision of wildlife corridors connecting the fragments.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] These can be a river, ditch, strip of trees, hedgerow or even an underpass to a highway.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Without the corridors, seeds cannot disperse and animals, especially small ones, cannot travel through the hostile territory, putting populations at greater risk of local extinction.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Habitat disturbance can have long-lasting effects on the environment.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] *Bromus tectorum* is a vigorous grass from Europe which has been introduced to the United States where it has become invasive.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] It is highly adapted to fire, producing large amounts of flammable detritus and increasing the frequency and intensity of wildfires.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] In areas where it has become established, it has altered the local fire regimen to such an extant that native plants cannot survive the frequent fires, allowing it to become even more dominant.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] A marine example is when sea urchin populations "explode" in coastal waters and destroy all the macroalgae present.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] What was previously a kelp forest becomes an urchin barren that may last for years and this can have a profound effect on the food chain.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Removal of the sea urchins, by disease for example, can result in the seaweed returning, with an over-abundance of fast-growing kelp.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Habitat fragmentation describes the emergence of discontinuities (fragmentation) in an organism's preferred environment (habitat), causing population fragmentation and ecosystem decay.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] More specifically, habitat fragmentation is a process by which large and contiguous habitats get divided into smaller, isolated patches of habitats.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Habitat destruction (also termed habitat loss) occurs when a natural habitat is no longer able to support its native species.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] The organisms once living there have either moved elsewhere, or are dead, leading to a decrease in biodiversity and species numbers.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Habitat destruction is in fact the leading cause of biodiversity loss and species extinction worldwide.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Humans contribute to habitat destruction through the use of natural resources, agriculture, industrial production and urbanization (urban sprawl).
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Other activities include mining, logging, and trawling.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Environmental factors can contribute to habitat destruction more indirectly.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Geological processes, climate change, introduction of invasive species, ecosystem nutrient depletion, water and noise pollution are some of the examples.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Loss of habitat can be preceded by an initial habitat fragmentation.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Fragmentation and loss of habitat have become one of the most important topics of research in ecology as they are major threats to the survival of endangered species.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] The protection of habitat types is a necessary step in the maintenance of biodiversity because if habitat destruction occurs, the animals and plants reliant on that habitat suffer.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Many countries have enacted legislation to protect their wildlife.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] This may take the form of the setting up of national parks, forest reserves and wildlife reserves, or it may restrict the activities of humans with the objective of benefiting wildlife.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] The laws may be designed to protect a particular species or group of species, or the legislation may prohibit such activities as the collecting of bird eggs, the hunting of animals or the removal of plants.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] A general law on the protection of habitat types may be more difficult to implement than a site specific requirement.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] A concept introduced in the United States in 1973 involves protecting the critical habitat of endangered species, and a similar concept has been incorporated into some Australian legislation.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] International treaties may be necessary for such objectives as the setting up of marine reserves.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Another international agreement, the Convention on the Conservation of Migratory Species of Wild Animals, protects animals that migrate across the globe and need protection in more than one country.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Even where legislation protects the environment, a lack of enforcement often prevents effective protection.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] However, the protection of habitat types needs to take into account the needs of the local residents for food, fuel and other resources.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Faced with hunger and destitution, a farmer is likely to plough up a level patch of ground despite it being the last suitable habitat for an endangered species such as the San Quintin kangaroo rat, and even kill the animal as a pest.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] In the interests of ecotourism it is desirable that local communities are educated on the uniqueness of their flora and fauna.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] A monotypic habitat type is a concept sometimes used in conservation biology, in which a single species of animal or plant is the only species of its type to be found in a specific habitat and forms a monoculture.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Even though it might seem such a habitat type is impoverished in biodiversity as compared with polytypic habitat types, this is not necessarily the case.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Monocultures of the exotic plant *Hydrilla* support a similarly rich fauna of invertebrates as a more varied habitat.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] The monotypic habitat occurs in both botanical and zoological contexts.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] Some invasive species may create monocultural stands that prevent other species from growing there.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] A dominant colonization can occur from retardant chemicals exuded, nutrient monopolization, or from lack of natural controls, such as herbivores or climate, that keep them in balance with their native habitat types.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] The yellow starthistle, *Centaurea solstitialis* is a botanical monotypic habitat example of this, currently dominating over 15,000,000 acres (61,000 km2) in California alone.
[src:shelf-break-front/habitat] The non-native freshwater zebra mussel, *Dreissena polymorpha*, that colonizes areas of the Great Lakes and the Mississippi River watershed, is a zoological monotypic habitat example; the predators or parasites that control it in its home-range in Russia are absent.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] There are more than 30 islands in the bay; the three largest ones are Aquidneck Island, Conanicut Island, and Prudence Island.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Bodies of water that are part of Narragansett Bay include the Sakonnet River, Mount Hope Bay, and the southern, tidal part of the Taunton River.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] The bay opens on Rhode Island Sound and the Atlantic Ocean; Block Island lies less than 20 miles (32 km) southwest of its opening.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] "Narragansett" is derived from the southern New England Algonquian word *Naiaganset* meaning "(people) of the small point of land".
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] The watershed of Narragansett Bay has seven river sub-drainage basins, including the Taunton, Pawtuxet, and Blackstone Rivers, and they provide freshwater input at approximately 2.1 million U.S. gallons (7.9×10^6 L) per day.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] River water inflow has a seasonal variability, with the highest flow in the spring and the minimum flow in early fall.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] The bay is a ria estuary (a drowned river valley) which is composed of the Sakonnet River valley, the East Passage river valley, and the West Passage river valley, which were formed of dropped crustal blocks in a horst and graben system that is slowly subsiding between a shifting fault system.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] The bathymetry varies greatly among the three passages, with the average depths of the East, West, and Sakonnet River passages being 121 feet (37 m), 33 feet (10 m), and 25 feet (7.6 m) respectively.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Providence is Rhode Island's capital and largest city and sits at the northernmost arm of the bay.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Many of Providence's suburbs are also on the bay, including East Providence, Warwick and Cranston.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Newport is located at the south end of Aquidneck Island on the ocean, and is the home of the United States Naval War College, the Naval Undersea Warfare Center, and a major United States Navy training center.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] The city of Fall River, Massachusetts is located at the confluence of the Taunton River and Mount Hope Bay, which form the northeasternmost part of Narragansett Bay.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] The southwest side of the bay includes the seaside tourist towns of Narragansett and Wickford.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Quonset Point, south of Warwick, gives its name to the Quonset hut.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Tides in the watershed are measured at Providence, Fall River, Quonset Point, Conimicut Light, Prudence Island, and Newport.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] In shallow water, sound waves are used to measure water height by precisely measuring their travel time.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] In deeper water, tides are measured with pressure-sensing tide gauges that are placed on the ocean floor to measure water height.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] The bay's tides are semi-diurnal, meaning that the region experiences two high and low tides daily.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] The tides range in height from 3.6 feet (1.1 m) at the bay's mouth and 4.6 feet (1.4 m) at its head.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Water depth varies about 4 feet (1.2 m) between high and low tide.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] The lunar, semi-diurnal M2 tide occurs at a period of 12.42 hours, with two tides occurring in the watershed every 24 hours and 50 minutes.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] The watershed's neap and spring tides occur every 14.8 days.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] In Narragansett bay, the tides show a distinct double-peak flood during high tide and single peak ebb during low tide.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] The movement of water within a system is its circulation.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Estuaries are given a classification depending on the pattern of their circulations.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] The circulation classification can be well-mixed, partially mixed, salt wedge, or Fjord-type.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] For Narragansett, the circulation is mostly well-mixed; however, the Providence River does show some vertical stratification.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Narragansett Bay circulation is made up of forces provided by the winds, tides, and changes in water density within the watershed.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Its circulation is the result of the flow of fresh water at the head interacting with salt water at the point where the bay meets the open ocean.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Residence time of water due to the circulation of Narragansett Bay is 10–40 days, with an average of 26 days.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Tidal mixing is the dominant driver of circulation patterns in the bay, where currents can reach up to 2.5 feet per second.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Non-tidal currents such as the flow of low salinity water at the surface out of the bay and high salinity deep water into the bay contribute to a current of about 0.33 feet per second.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Winds also drive circulation patterns in the bay.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] In the winter, winds come from the northwest, helping move water towards the bay's mouth; in the summer, they are out of the southwest and move water towards the head of the bay.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Wind-driven waves of over 4.25 feet (1.30 m) also help mix surface waters.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Density-driven forces are the third factor affecting circulation.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Fresh water inflow comes from natural sources such as atmospheric precipitation and inflow from the many rivers that feed into the watershed, and human-made sources such as water treatment plants.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Fresh and saltwater mixing results in a salinity range in the bay of 24 parts per thousand (ppt) in the upper Providence River area to 32 ppt at the mouth of the bay.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] The bay's currents and circulation patterns greatly influence the sediment deposits within the region.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] The majority of the sediments within the bay are fine-grained material such as detritus, clay-silt, and sand-silt-clay.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] The first visit by Europeans to the bay was probably in the early 16th century.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] At the time, the area surrounding the bay was inhabited by two different Indian tribes: the Narragansetts occupied the west side of the bay, and the Wampanoags lived on the east side, occupying the land east to Cape Cod.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] It is accepted by most historians that first contact by Europeans was made by Giovanni da Verrazzano, an Italian explorer who entered the bay in his ship *La Dauphine* in 1524 after visiting New York Bay.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Verrazzano called the bay *Refugio*, the "Refuge".
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] It has several entrances, however, and historians can only speculate as to the exact route of his voyage and the location where he laid anchor, along with a corresponding uncertainty over which tribe made contact with him.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Verrazzano reported that he found clearings and open forests suitable for travel "even by a large army".
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Dutch navigator Adriaen Block explored and mapped the bay in 1614, and nearby Block Island is named in his honor.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] The first permanent Colonial settlement was established in 1636 by Roger Williams, a former member of the Massachusetts Bay Colony.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] He was friends with Narragansett *sachem* Canonicus, who provided him with land on which to build Providence Plantations.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Around the same time, the Dutch established a trading post approximately 12 miles (20 km) to the southwest which was under the authority of New Amsterdam in New York Bay.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] In 1643, Williams traveled to England and was granted a charter for the Colony of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] The Gaspee Affair was an important naval event which moved the Thirteen Colonies toward the American Revolution.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] It occurred in Narragansett Bay in 1772 and involved the capture and burning of the British customs schooner *Gaspee*.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] The American victory contributed to the eventual start of the war at the Battles of Lexington and Concord in Massachusetts three years later.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] The event is celebrated in Pawtuxet Village as the Gaspee Days Celebration in June which includes burning the ship in effigy.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Roger Williams and other early colonists named the islands Prudence, Patience, Hope, Despair, and Hog.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] To remember the names, colonial school children often recited the poem: "Patience, Prudence, Hope, and Despair.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Narragansett Bay is divided by Conanicut Island into east and west passages.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Its depth averages approximately 9.0 meters throughout the bay, but it is shallower in the west passage and deeper in the east.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Narragansett Bay receives freshwater input from several sources, including rivers (approximately 80%), direct precipitation (13%), wastewater treatment facilities (9%), and unknown amounts from ground-water and combined sewer overflows (CSOs).
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] The freshwater input varies greatly from season to season as it is highest in winter and lowest in summer, while CSOs increase dramatically following heavy rain.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Water from these freshwater inputs mixes with sea water to form a salinity gradient ranging from 24 ppt at the mouth of the Providence River to 32 ppt at the mouth of the bay.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Water temperatures range between -0.5 °C and 24 °C over the year.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Dissolved oxygen levels in Narragansett Bay are seasonal with lower levels in the summer and higher levels in the winter.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] This is due to warmer temperatures and higher biological demand for oxygen in the summer and the opposite in the winter.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Narragansett Bay is also subject to periodic summer hypoxic events in the Northern half of the bay, nearing anoxic conditions in some parts.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Phytoplankton forms the base of the food chain for many of the bay's marine animals.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] General trends in phytoplankton biomass across the bay are characterized by highest levels in the Providence River and lowest levels in Rhode Island Sound, correlating with the North to South nutrient concentration gradient in the bay (24).
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Near the Providence River, biomass levels are highest in the summer and lowest in the winter.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] In the east and west passages there are peaks in the spring and fall.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Annual blooms have shrunk over the last decade (2006 onward) as the amount of nitrogen (an important nutrient) supply to the bay has decreased by more than 50% due to wastewater treatment facilities switching to a new treatment that involves removal of nitrogen.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Narragansett Bay is the site of one of the world's longest-running plankton surveys, extending from 1957 through the present.
[src:shelf-break-front/narragansett-bay] Researchers at the University of Rhode Island’s Graduate School of Oceanography collect samples weekly and the dataset contains 246 different species.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Phytoplankton obtain their energy through photosynthesis, as trees and other plants do on land.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] This means phytoplankton must receive sunlight, so they live in the well-lit surface layers (euphotic zone) of oceans and lakes.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Compared with terrestrial plants, phytoplankton are distributed over a larger surface area, experience less seasonal variation, and have markedly faster turnover rates (days versus decades).
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] As a result, phytoplankton respond rapidly on a global scale to climate variations.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Phytoplankton form the base of marine and freshwater food webs and are key players in the global carbon cycle.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] They account for about half of global photosynthetic activity and at least half of the oxygen production, despite amounting to only about 1% of the global plant biomass.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Phytoplankton are very diverse, comprising photosynthesizing bacteria (cyanobacteria) and various unicellular protist groups (notably the diatoms).
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Most phytoplankton are too small to be individually seen with the unaided eye.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] However, when present in sufficient numbers, some varieties may appear as colored patches on the water surface due to chlorophyll in their cells and, in some species, accessory pigments (such as phycobiliproteins or xanthophylls).
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Phytoplankton are photosynthesizing microscopic protists and bacteria that inhabit the upper sunlit layer of marine and freshwater bodies of water on Earth.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Paralleling plants on land, phytoplankton undertake primary production in water, creating organic compounds from carbon dioxide dissolved in the water.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Phytoplankton form the base of — and sustain — the aquatic food web, and are crucial players in the Earth's carbon cycle.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Many other organism groups formerly named as phytoplankton, including coccolithophores and dinoflagellates, are now no longer included as they are not only phototrophic but can also eat other organisms.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] These organisms are now more correctly termed mixoplankton.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] This recognition has important consequences for how the functioning of the planktonic food web is viewed.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Phytoplankton obtain energy through the process of photosynthesis and must therefore live in the well-lit surface layer (termed the euphotic zone) of an ocean, sea, lake, or other body of water.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Phytoplankton account for about half of all photosynthetic activity on Earth.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Their cumulative energy fixation in carbon compounds (primary production) is the basis for the vast majority of oceanic and also many freshwater food webs (chemosynthesis is a notable exception).
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] While almost all phytoplankton species are obligate photoautotrophs, some are mixotrophic and other, non-pigmented species that are actually heterotrophic (the latter are often viewed as zooplankton).
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Of these, the best known are dinoflagellate genera such as *Noctiluca* and *Dinophysis*, that obtain organic carbon by ingesting other organisms or detrital material.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Phytoplankton live in the photic zone of the ocean, where photosynthesis is possible.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] During photosynthesis, they assimilate carbon dioxide and release oxygen.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] If solar radiation is too high, phytoplankton may fall victim to photodegradation.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Phytoplankton species feature a large variety of photosynthetic pigments, which enable them to absorb different wavelengths of the variable underwater light.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] This implies different species can use the wavelength of light differently efficiently.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] The light is not a single ecological resource but a multitude of resources depending on its spectral composition.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] By that it was found that changes in the spectrum of light alone can alter natural phytoplankton communities even if the same intensity is available.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] For growth, phytoplankton cells additionally depend on nutrients, which enter the ocean by rivers, continental weathering, and glacial ice meltwater on the poles.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Phytoplankton release dissolved organic carbon (DOC) into the sea.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Since phytoplankton are the basis of marine food webs, they serve as prey for zooplankton, fish larvae, and other heterotrophic organisms.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] They can also be degraded by bacteria or by viral lysis.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Although some phytoplankton cells, such as dinoflagellates, can migrate vertically, they are still incapable of actively moving against currents, so they slowly sink and ultimately fertilize the seafloor with dead cells and detritus.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Phytoplankton are crucially dependent on several nutrients.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] These are primarily macronutrients such as nitrate, phosphate, or silicic acid, which are required in relatively large quantities for growth.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Their availability in the surface ocean is governed by the balance between the so-called biological pump and upwelling of deep, nutrient-rich waters.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] The stoichiometric nutrient composition of phytoplankton drives — and is driven by — the Redfield ratio of macronutrients generally available throughout the surface oceans.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Phytoplankton also rely on trace metals, such as iron (Fe), manganese (Mn), zinc (Zn), cobalt (Co), cadmium (Cd), and copper (Cu), as essential micronutrients, which influence their growth and community composition.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Limitations in these metals can lead to co-limitations and shifts in phytoplankton community structure.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Across large areas of the oceans such as the Southern Ocean, phytoplankton are often limited by the lack of the micronutrient iron.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] This has led to some scientists advocating iron fertilization as a means to counteract the accumulation of human-produced carbon dioxide (CO2) in the atmosphere.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Large-scale experiments have added iron (usually as salts such as ferrous sulfate) to the oceans to promote phytoplankton growth and draw atmospheric CO2 into the ocean.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Controversy over ecosystem manipulation and the efficiency of iron fertilization has slowed such experiments.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] The ocean science community still has a divided attitude toward the study of iron fertilization as a potential marine Carbon Dioxide Removal (mCDR) approach.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Phytoplankton depend on B vitamins for survival.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Areas in the ocean have been identified as having a major deficiency of certain B Vitamins and, correspondingly, phytoplankton.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] The effects of anthropogenic warming on the global phytoplankton population are an area of active research.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Changes in the vertical stratification of the water column, the rate of temperature-dependent biological reactions, and the atmospheric supply of nutrients are expected to have important effects on future phytoplankton productivity.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] The effects of anthropogenic ocean acidification on phytoplankton growth and community structure have also received considerable attention.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] The cells of coccolithophore phytoplankton are typically covered in a calcium carbonate shell called a coccosphere that is sensitive to ocean acidification.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Because of their short generation times, evidence suggests that some phytoplankton can adapt to pH changes induced by increased carbon dioxide on rapid time scales (months to years).
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Phytoplankton serve as the base of the aquatic food web, providing an essential ecological function for all aquatic life.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Under future conditions of anthropogenic warming and ocean acidification, changes in phytoplankton mortality due to changes in rates of zooplankton grazing may be significant.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] One of the many food chains in the ocean – remarkable due to the small number of links – is that of phytoplankton sustaining krill (a crustacean similar to a tiny shrimp), which in turn sustain baleen whales.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] The El Niño-Southern Oscillation (ENSO) cycles in the Equatorial Pacific area can affect phytoplankton.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Biochemical and physical changes during ENSO cycles modify the phytoplankton community structure.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Also, changes in the structure of the phytoplankton, such as a significant reduction in biomass and phytoplankton density, particularly during El Niño phases, can occur.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] The sensitivity of phytoplankton to environmental changes is why they are often used as indicators of estuarine and coastal ecological condition and health.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] To study these events, satellite ocean color observations are used to observe these changes.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Satellite images help to have a better view of their global distribution.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Phytoplankton concentrates along the boundaries of the eddies, tracing the motion of the water.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] The term phytoplankton encompasses all photoautotrophic microorganisms in aquatic food webs.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] However, unlike terrestrial communities, where most autotrophs are plants, phytoplankton are a diverse group, incorporating protistan eukaryotes and both eubacterial and archaebacterial prokaryotes.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] There are about 5,000 known species of marine phytoplankton.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] How such diversity evolved despite scarce resources (restricting niche differentiation) is unclear.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] In terms of numbers, the most important groups of phytoplankton include the diatoms, cyanobacteria and dinoflagellates, although many other groups of algae are represented.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] One group, the coccolithophorids, is responsible (in part) for the release of significant amounts of dimethyl sulfide (DMS) into the atmosphere.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] DMS is oxidized to form sulfate which, in areas where ambient aerosol particle concentrations are low, can contribute to the population of cloud condensation nuclei, mostly leading to increased cloud cover and cloud albedo according to the so-called CLAW hypothesis.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Different types of phytoplankton support different trophic levels within varying ecosystems.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Within more productive ecosystems, dominated by upwelling or high terrestrial inputs, larger dinoflagellates are the more dominant phytoplankton and reflect a larger portion of the biomass.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] In the early twentieth century, Alfred C.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Redfield found the similarity of the phytoplankton's elemental composition to the major dissolved nutrients in the deep ocean.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Redfield proposed that the ratio of carbon to nitrogen to phosphorus (106:16:1) in the ocean was controlled by the phytoplankton's requirements, as phytoplankton subsequently release nitrogen and phosphorus as they are remineralized.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] This so-called "Redfield ratio" in describing the stoichiometry of phytoplankton and seawater has become a fundamental principle for understanding marine ecology, biogeochemistry, and phytoplankton evolution.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] However, the Redfield ratio is not a universal value and it may diverge due to the changes in exogenous nutrient delivery and microbial metabolisms in the ocean, such as nitrogen fixation, denitrification and anammox.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] The dynamic stoichiometry observed in unicellular algae reflects their ability to store nutrients in an internal pool, shift between enzymes with varying nutrient requirements, and alter osmolyte composition.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Different cellular components have their own unique stoichiometry characteristics, for instance, resource (light or nutrients) acquisition machinery such as proteins and chlorophyll contain a high concentration of nitrogen but low in phosphorus.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Meanwhile, growth machinery, such as ribosomal RNA, contains high concentrations of nitrogen and phosphorus.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Based on allocation of resources, phytoplankton is classified into three different growth strategies, namely survivalist, bloomer and generalist.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Survivalist phytoplankton have a high N:P ratio (>30) and possess abundant machinery for resource acquisition to sustain growth under resource scarcity.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Bloomer phytoplankton has a low N:P ratio (<10), contains a high proportion of growth machinery, and is adapted to exponential growth.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Generalist phytoplankton have N:P ratios similar to the Redfield ratio and contain relatively equal resource-acquisition and growth machinery.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] The study focused on the sub-arctic region of the North Atlantic Ocean, which is the site of one of Earth's largest recurring phytoplankton blooms.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] The long history of research in this location, as well as the relative ease of accessibility, made the North Atlantic an ideal location to test prevailing scientific hypotheses in an effort to better understand the role of phytoplankton aerosol emissions on Earth's energy budget.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] NAAMES was designed to target specific phases of the annual phytoplankton cycle: minimum, climax, and the intermediary decreasing and increasing biomass, to resolve debates on the timing of bloom formations and the patterns driving annual bloom re-creation.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] The NAAMES project also investigated the quantity, size, and composition of aerosols generated by primary production to understand how phytoplankton bloom cycles affect cloud formations and climate.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Phytoplankton are the key mediators of the biological pump.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Understanding phytoplankton's response to changing environmental conditions is a prerequisite for predicting future atmospheric CO2 concentrations.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Temperature, irradiance, nutrient concentrations, and CO2 are the chief environmental factors that influence the physiology and stoichiometry of phytoplankton.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] The stoichiometry or elemental composition of phytoplankton is of utmost importance to secondary producers such as copepods, fish and shrimp, because it determines the nutritional quality and influences energy flow through the marine food chains.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Climate change may greatly restructure phytoplankton communities leading to cascading consequences for marine food webs, thereby altering the amount of carbon transported to the ocean interior.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] The figure provides an overview of the environmental factors that collectively affect phytoplankton productivity.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] All of these factors are expected to undergo significant changes in the future ocean due to global change.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Global warming simulations predict oceanic temperature increase; dramatic changes in oceanic stratification, circulation and changes in cloud cover and sea ice, resulting in an increased light supply to the ocean surface.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Also, reduced nutrient supply is predicted to co-occur with ocean acidification and warming, due to increased water-column stratification and reduced nutrient mixing from deep waters to the surface.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] The compartments influenced by phytoplankton include atmospheric gas composition, inorganic nutrients, trace-element fluxes, and the transfer and cycling of organic matter via biological processes (see figure).
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Photosynthetically fixed carbon is rapidly recycled and reused in the surface ocean.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] At the same time, a certain fraction of this biomass is exported as sinking particles to the deep sea, where it is subject to ongoing transformation processes, e.g., remineralization.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Phytoplankton contribute not only to a basic pelagic marine food web but also to the microbial loop.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Phytoplankton are the base of the marine food web, and because they do not rely on other organisms for food, they make up the first trophic level.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Organisms such as zooplankton feed on these phytoplankton, which are in turn fed on by other organisms, and so on, until the fourth trophic level is reached, with apex predators.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Approximately 90% of total carbon is lost between trophic levels due to respiration, detritus, and dissolved organic matter.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] This underscores the importance of the remineralization process and nutrient cycling performed by phytoplankton and bacteria in maintaining efficiency.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Phytoplankton blooms in which a species increases rapidly under conditions favorable to growth can produce harmful algal blooms (HABs).
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Phytoplankton are a key food item in both aquaculture and mariculture.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Both utilize phytoplankton as food for the animals being farmed.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] In mariculture, phytoplankton is naturally occurring and introduced into enclosures through the normal seawater circulation.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] In aquaculture, phytoplankton must be obtained and introduced directly.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Plankton can be collected from a body of water or cultured, though the former method is rarely used.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Phytoplankton is used as a foodstock for the production of rotifers, which are in turn used to feed other organisms.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Phytoplankton is also used to feed wide varieties of aquacultured molluscs, including pearl oysters and giant clams.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] The production of phytoplankton under controlled conditions constitutes a form of aquaculture.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Phytoplankton is cultured for a variety of purposes, including foodstock for other aquacultured organisms, a nutritional supplement for captive invertebrates in aquaria.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Culture sizes range from small-scale laboratory cultures of less than one litre to tens of thousands of litres in commercial aquaculture.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Regardless of the size of the culture, certain conditions must be provided for efficient growth of plankton.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] The majority of cultured plankton is marine, and seawater of a specific gravity of 1.010 to 1.026 may be used as a culture medium.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] This water must be sterilized, usually by either high temperatures in an autoclave or by exposure to ultraviolet radiation, to prevent biological contamination of the culture.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Various fertilizers are added to the culture medium to promote plankton growth.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] A culture must be aerated or agitated in some way to keep plankton suspended, as well as to provide dissolved carbon dioxide for photosynthesis.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] In addition to constant aeration, most cultures are manually mixed or stirred regularly.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Light is required for phytoplankton growth.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] The color temperature of illumination should be approximately 6,500 K, but values from 4,000 K to 20,000 K or higher have been used successfully.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] The duration of light exposure should be approximately 16 hours daily; this is the most efficient artificial day length.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Marine phytoplankton perform half of the global photosynthetic CO2 fixation (net global primary production of ~50 Pg C per year) and half of the oxygen production despite amounting to only ~1% of global plant biomass.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] In comparison with terrestrial plants, marine phytoplankton are distributed over a larger surface area, are exposed to less seasonal variation, and have markedly faster turnover rates than trees (days versus decades).
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Therefore, phytoplankton respond rapidly on a global scale to climate variations.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] These characteristics are important when evaluating phytoplankton contributions to carbon fixation and forecasting how this production may change in response to perturbations.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Predicting the effects of climate change on primary productivity is complicated by phytoplankton bloom cycles, which are influenced by both bottom-up (e.g., nutrient availability and vertical mixing) and top-down (e.g., grazing and viral control) factors.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Increases in solar radiation, temperature and freshwater inputs to surface waters strengthen ocean stratification and consequently reduce transport of nutrients from deep water to surface waters, which reduces primary productivity.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Conversely, rising CO2 levels can increase phytoplankton primary production, but only when nutrients are not limiting.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Some studies indicate that global phytoplankton density has decreased over the past century.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Still, these conclusions have been questioned due to the limited availability of long-term phytoplankton data, methodological differences in data generation, and the pronounced annual and decadal variability in phytoplankton production.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Moreover, other studies suggest a global increase in oceanic phytoplankton production and changes in specific regions or specific phytoplankton groups.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] The global Sea Ice Index is declining, leading to higher light penetration and potentially more primary production; however, there are conflicting predictions for the effects of variable mixing patterns and changes in nutrient supply and for productivity trends in polar zones.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] The effect of human-caused climate change on phytoplankton biodiversity remains poorly understood.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Should greenhouse gas emissions continue rising to high levels by 2100, some phytoplankton models predict an increase in species richness, or the number of different species within a given area.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] This increase in plankton diversity is traced to warming ocean temperatures.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] In addition to changes in species richness, the distribution of phytoplankton is expected to shift towards the Earth's poles.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Such movement may disrupt ecosystems because phytoplankton are consumed by zooplankton, which in turn sustain fisheries.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] This shift in phytoplankton distribution may also diminish their ability to sequester carbon emitted by human activities.
[src:shelf-break-front/phytoplankton] Human (anthropogenic) changes to phytoplankton impact both natural and economic processes.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] In physics, **potential energy** is the energy of an object or system due to the body's position relative to other objects, or the configuration of its particles.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The energy is equal to the work done against any restoring forces, such as gravity or those in a spring.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The term *potential energy* was introduced by the 19th-century Scottish engineer and physicist William Rankine, although it has links to the ancient Greek philosopher Aristotle's concept of *potentiality*.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Common types of potential energy include gravitational potential energy, the elastic potential energy of a deformed spring, and the electric potential energy of an electric charge and an electric field.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The unit for energy in the International System of Units (SI) is the joule (symbol J).
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Potential energy is associated with forces that act on a body in a way that the total work done by these forces on the body depends only on the initial and final positions of the body in space.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] These forces, whose total work is path independent, are called *conservative forces*.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] If the force acting on a body varies over space, then one has a *force field*; such a field is described by vectors at every point in space, which is, in turn, called a *vector field*.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] A conservative vector field can be simply expressed as the gradient of a certain scalar function, called a *scalar potential*.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The potential energy is related to, and can be obtained from, this potential function.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] There are various types of potential energy, each associated with a particular type of force.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Chemical potential energy, such as the energy stored in fossil fuels, is the work of the Coulomb force during rearrangement of configurations of electrons and nuclei in atoms and molecules.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Thermal energy usually has two components: the kinetic energy of random motions of particles and the potential energy of their configuration.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Forces derivable from a potential are also called conservative forces.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The work done by a conservative force is $W=-\Delta U,$ where $\Delta U$ is the change in the potential energy associated with the force.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The negative sign provides the convention that work done against a force field increases potential energy, while work done by the force field decreases potential energy.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Common notations for potential energy are *PE*, *U*, *V*, and *E*p.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Potential energy is the energy by virtue of an object's position relative to other objects.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Potential energy is often associated with restoring forces such as a spring or the force of gravity.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The action of stretching a spring or lifting a mass is performed by an external force that works against the force field of the potential.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] This work is stored in the force field, which is said to be stored as potential energy.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] If the external force is removed the force field acts on the body to perform the work as it moves the body back to the initial position, reducing the stretch of the spring or causing a body to fall.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Consider a ball whose mass is *m* dropped from height *h*.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The acceleration *g* of free fall is approximately constant, so the weight force of the ball *mg* is constant.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The more formal definition is that potential energy is the energy difference between the energy of an object in a given position and its energy at a reference position.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] From around 1840 scientists sought to define and understand energy and work.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The term "potential energy" was coined by William Rankine, a Scottish engineer and physicist, in 1853 as part of a specific effort to develop terminology.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] He chose the term as part of the pair "actual" vs "potential" going back to work by Aristotle.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] In his 1867 discussion of the same topic Rankine describes potential energy as 'energy of configuration' in contrast to actual energy as 'energy of activity'.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Also in 1867, William Thomson introduced "kinetic energy" as the opposite of "potential energy", asserting that all actual energy took the form of ⁠1/2⁠*mv*2.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Once this hypothesis became widely accepted, the term "actual energy" gradually faded.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Potential energy is closely linked with forces in conservative fields.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] If the work done by a force on a body that moves from *A* to *B* does not depend on the path between these points (if the work is done by a conservative force), then the work of this force measured from *A* assigns a scalar value to every other point in space and defines a scalar potential field.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] In this case, the force can be defined as the negative of the vector gradient of the potential field.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] If the work for an applied force is independent of the path, then the work done by the force is evaluated from the start to the end of the trajectory of the point of application.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] This means that there is a function *U*(**x**), called a "potential", that can be evaluated at the two points **x**A and **x**B to obtain the work over any trajectory between these two points.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] It is tradition to define this function with a negative sign so that positive work is a reduction in the potential, that is $W=\int _{C}\mathbf {F} \cdot d\mathbf {x} =U(\mathbf {x} _{\text{A}})-U(\mathbf {x} _{\text{B}})$ where *C* is the trajectory taken from A to B.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Because the work done is independent of the path taken, then this expression is true for any trajectory, *C*, from A to B.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The function *U*(**x**) is called the potential energy associated with the applied force.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Examples of forces that have potential energies are gravity and spring forces.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] In this section the relationship between work and potential energy is presented in more detail.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] This means the work integral does not depend on the path between A and B and is said to be independent of the path.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] In this case, the application of the del operator to the work function yields, ${\nabla W}=-{\nabla U}=-\left({\frac {\partial U}{\partial x}},{\frac {\partial U}{\partial y}},{\frac {\partial U}{\partial z}}\right)=\mathbf {F} ,$ and the force **F** is said to be "derivable from a potential".
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] This also necessarily implies that **F** must be a conservative vector field.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The potential *U* defines a force **F** at every point **x** in space, so the set of forces is called a force field.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Given a force field **F**(**x**), evaluation of the work integral using the gradient theorem can be used to find the scalar function associated with potential energy.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Examples of work that can be computed from potential functions are gravity and spring forces.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] For small height changes, gravitational potential energy can be computed using $U_{\text{g}}=mgh,$ where *m* is the mass in kilograms, *g* is the local gravitational field (9.8 metres per second squared on Earth), *h* is the height above a reference level in metres, and *U* is the energy in joules.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] In classical physics, gravity exerts a constant downward force ***F*** = (0, 0, *F*z) on the center of mass of a body moving near the surface of the Earth.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The work of gravity depends only on the vertical movement of the curve ***r***(*t*).
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] A horizontal spring exerts a force **F** = (−*kx*, 0, 0) that is proportional to its deformation in the axial or *x*-direction.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The function $U(x)={\frac {1}{2}}kx^{2},$ is called the potential energy of a linear spring.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Elastic potential energy is the potential energy of an elastic object (for example a bow or a catapult) that is deformed under tension or compression (or stressed in formal terminology).
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] It arises as a consequence of a force that tries to restore the object to its original shape, which is most often the electromagnetic force between the atoms and molecules that constitute the object.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] If the stretch is released, the energy is transformed into kinetic energy.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The negative sign follows the convention that work is gained from a loss of potential energy.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The potential energy is a function of the state a system is in, and is defined relative to that for a particular state.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] This reference state is not always a real state; it may also be a limit, such as with the distances between all bodies tending to infinity, provided that the energy involved in tending to that limit is finite, such as in the case of inverse-square law forces.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Any arbitrary reference state could be used; therefore it can be chosen based on convenience.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Typically the potential energy of a system depends on the *relative* positions of its components only, so the reference state can also be expressed in terms of relative positions.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Gravitational energy is the potential energy associated with gravitational force, as work is required to elevate objects against Earth's gravity.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The potential energy due to elevated positions is called gravitational potential energy, and is evidenced by water in an elevated reservoir or kept behind a dam.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] If an object falls from one point to another point inside a gravitational field, the force of gravity will do positive work on the object, and the gravitational potential energy will decrease by the same amount.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Consider a book placed on top of a table.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] As the book is raised from the floor to the table, some external force works against the gravitational force.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] If the book falls back to the floor, the "falling" energy the book receives is provided by the gravitational force.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Thus, if the book falls off the table, this potential energy goes to accelerate the mass of the book and is converted into kinetic energy.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] When the book hits the floor this kinetic energy is converted into heat, deformation, and sound by the impact.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The factors that affect an object's gravitational potential energy are its height relative to some reference point, its mass, and the strength of the gravitational field it is in.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Thus, a book lying on a table has less gravitational potential energy than the same book on top of a taller cupboard and less gravitational potential energy than a heavier book lying on the same table.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] An object at a certain height above the Moon's surface has less gravitational potential energy than at the same height above the Earth's surface because the Moon's gravity is weaker.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] "Height" in the common sense of the term cannot be used for gravitational potential energy calculations when gravity is not assumed to be a constant.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The following sections provide more detail.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The strength of a gravitational field varies with location.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] However, when the change of distance is small in relation to the distances from the center of the source of the gravitational field, this variation in field strength is negligible and we can assume that the force of gravity on a particular object is constant.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Near the surface of the Earth, for example, we assume that the acceleration due to gravity is a constant *g* = 9.8 m/s2 (standard gravity).
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The amount of gravitational potential energy held by an elevated object is equal to the work done against gravity in lifting it.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The work done equals the force required to move it upward multiplied with the vertical distance it is moved (remember *W* = *Fd*).
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The upward force required while moving at a constant velocity is equal to the weight, *mg*, of an object, so the work done in lifting it through a height h is the product *mgh*.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Thus, when accounting only for mass, gravity, and altitude, the equation is: $U=mgh$ where *U* is the potential energy of the object relative to its being on the Earth's surface, *m* is the mass of the object, *g* is the acceleration due to gravity, and *h* is the altitude of the object.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] However, over large variations in distance, the approximation that *g* is constant is no longer valid, and we have to use calculus and the general mathematical definition of work to determine gravitational potential energy.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] For the computation of the potential energy, we can integrate the gravitational force, whose magnitude is given by Newton's law of gravitation, with respect to the distance *r* between the two bodies.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Using that definition, the gravitational potential energy of a system of masses *m*1 and *M*2 at a distance *r* using the Newtonian constant of gravitation *G* is $U=-G{\frac {m_{1}M_{2}}{r}}+K,$ where *K* is an arbitrary constant dependent on the choice of datum from which potential is measured.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Choosing the convention that *K* = 0 (i.e. in relation to a point at infinity) makes calculations simpler, albeit at the cost of making *U* negative; for why this is physically reasonable, see below.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Given this formula for *U*, the total potential energy of a system of n bodies is found by summing, for all ${\textstyle {\frac {n(n-1)}{2}}}$ pairs of two bodies, the potential energy of the system of those two bodies.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Considering the system of bodies as the combined set of small particles the bodies consist of, and applying the previous on the particle level we get the negative gravitational binding energy.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] This potential energy is more strongly negative than the total potential energy of the system of bodies as such since it also includes the negative gravitational binding energy of each body.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] As with all potential energies, only differences in gravitational potential energy matter for most physical purposes, and the choice of zero point is arbitrary.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Given that there is no reasonable criterion for preferring one particular finite *r* over another, there seem to be only two reasonable choices for the distance at which *U* becomes zero: $r=0$ and $r=\infty$ .
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The choice of $U=0$ at infinity may seem peculiar, and the consequence that gravitational energy is always negative may seem counterintuitive, but this choice allows gravitational potential energy values to be finite, albeit negative.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Since physicists abhor infinities in their calculations, and *r* is always non-zero in practice, the choice of $U=0$ at infinity is by far the more preferable choice, even if the idea of negative energy in a gravity well appears to be peculiar at first.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The negative value for gravitational energy also has deeper implications that make it seem more reasonable in cosmological calculations where the total energy of the universe can meaningfully be considered; see inflation theory for more on this.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Gravitational potential energy has a number of practical uses, notably the generation of pumped-storage hydroelectricity.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] For example, in Dinorwig, Wales, there are two lakes, one at a higher elevation than the other.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] At times when surplus electricity is not required (and so is comparatively cheap), water is pumped up to the higher lake, thus converting the electrical energy (running the pump) to gravitational potential energy.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] At times of peak demand for electricity, the water flows back down through electrical generator turbines, converting the potential energy into kinetic energy and then back into electricity.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The process is not completely efficient and some of the original energy from the surplus electricity is in fact lost to friction.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Gravitational potential energy is also used to power clocks in which falling weights operate the mechanism.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] It is also used by counterweights for lifting up an elevator, crane, or sash window.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Roller coasters are an entertaining way to utilize potential energy – chains are used to move a car up an incline (building up gravitational potential energy), to then have that energy converted into kinetic energy as it falls.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Another practical use is utilizing gravitational potential energy to descend (perhaps coast) downhill in transportation such as the descent of an automobile, truck, railroad train, bicycle, airplane, or fluid in a pipeline.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] In some cases the kinetic energy obtained from the potential energy of descent may be used to start ascending the next grade such as what happens when a road is undulating and has frequent dips.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The commercialization of stored energy (in the form of rail cars raised to higher elevations) that is then converted to electrical energy when needed by an electrical grid, is being undertaken in the United States in a system called Advanced Rail Energy Storage (ARES).
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Chemical potential energy is a form of potential energy related to the structural arrangement of atoms or molecules.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] This arrangement may be the result of chemical bonds within a molecule or otherwise.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Chemical energy of a chemical substance can be transformed to other forms of energy by a chemical reaction.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] As an example, when a fuel is burned the chemical energy is converted to heat, same is the case with digestion of food metabolized in a biological organism.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Green plants transform solar energy to chemical energy through the process known as photosynthesis, and electrical energy can be converted to chemical energy through electrochemical reactions.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The similar term chemical potential is used to indicate the potential of a substance to undergo a change of configuration, be it in the form of a chemical reaction, spatial transport, particle exchange with a reservoir, etc.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] An object can have potential energy by virtue of its electric charge and several forces related to their presence.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] There are two main types of this kind of potential energy: electrostatic potential energy, electrodynamic potential energy (also sometimes called magnetic potential energy).
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] If the electric charge of an object can be assumed to be at rest, then it has potential energy due to its position relative to other charged objects.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The electrostatic potential energy is the energy of an electrically charged particle (at rest) in an electric field.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] It is defined as the work that must be done to move it from an infinite distance away to its present location, adjusted for non-electrical forces on the object.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] This energy will generally be non-zero if there is another electrically charged object nearby.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The work *W* required to move *q* from *A* to any point *B* in the electrostatic force field is given by $\Delta U_{AB}({\mathbf {r} })=-\int _{A}^{B}\mathbf {F_{e}} \cdot d\mathbf {r}$ typically given in J for Joules.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] A related quantity called *electric potential* (commonly denoted with a *V* for voltage) is equal to the electric potential energy per unit charge.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The magnetization **M** in a field is $U=-{\frac {1}{2}}\int \mathbf {M} \cdot \mathbf {B} \,dV,$ where the integral can be over all space or, equivalently, where **M** is nonzero.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Magnetic potential energy is the form of energy related not only to the distance between magnetic materials, but also to the orientation, or alignment, of those materials within the field.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] For example, the needle of a compass has the lowest magnetic potential energy when it is aligned with the north and south poles of the Earth's magnetic field.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] If the needle is moved by an outside force, torque is exerted on the magnetic dipole of the needle by the Earth's magnetic field, causing it to move back into alignment.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The magnetic potential energy of the needle is highest when its field is in the same direction as the Earth's magnetic field.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Two magnets will have potential energy in relation to each other and the distance between them, but this also depends on their orientation.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] If the opposite poles are held apart, the potential energy will be higher the further they are apart and lower the closer they are.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Conversely, like poles will have the highest potential energy when forced together, and the lowest when they spring apart.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Nuclear potential energy is the potential energy of the particles inside an atomic nucleus.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The nuclear particles are bound together by the strong nuclear force.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Their rest mass provides the potential energy for certain kinds of radioactive decay, such as beta decay.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Nuclear particles like protons and neutrons are not destroyed in fission and fusion processes, but collections of them can have less mass than if they were individually free, in which case this mass difference can be liberated as heat and radiation in nuclear reactions.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The process of hydrogen fusion occurring in the Sun is an example of this form of energy release – 600 million tonnes of hydrogen nuclei are fused into helium nuclei, with a loss of about 4 million tonnes of mass per second.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] This energy, now in the form of kinetic energy and gamma rays, keeps the solar core hot even as electromagnetic radiation carries electromagnetic energy into space.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] Potential energy is closely linked with forces.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] If the work done by a force on a body that moves from *A* to *B* does not depend on the path between these points, then the work of this force measured from *A* assigns a scalar value to every other point in space and defines a scalar potential field.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] For example, gravity is a conservative force.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] The associated potential is the gravitational potential, often denoted by $\phi$ or V , corresponding to the energy per unit mass as a function of position.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] In practical terms, this means that one can set the zero of U and $\phi$ anywhere one likes.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] One may set it to be zero at the surface of the Earth, or may find it more convenient to set zero at infinity (as in the expressions given earlier in this section).
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] A conservative force can be expressed in the language of differential geometry as a closed form.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] As Euclidean space is contractible, its de Rham cohomology vanishes, so every closed form is also an exact form, and can be expressed as the gradient of a scalar field.
[src:shelf-break-front/potential-energy] This gives a mathematical justification of the fact that all conservative forces are gradients of a potential field.
[src:shelf-break-front/shelf-break-front] The energy terms can be expressed in very detailed equations, but with constant terms factored out, the important terms are water velocity (average velocity, $\left\vert {\bar {U}}\right\vert$ ) and water depth (h).
[src:shelf-break-front/shelf-break-front] Where $C_{D}$ is a friction coefficient, approximated as 0.003 for a sandy bottom.
[src:shelf-break-front/shelf-break-front] This index can be calculated for any coastal region, usually in the range of +3 (highly stratified) to -2 (highly turbulent).
[src:shelf-break-front/shelf-break-front] The stratification index for a Shelf Break Front is an indication of how productive phytoplankton will be.
[src:shelf-break-front/shelf-break-front] When the stratification index is approximately 1.5, this produces a nutrient-rich environment for the growth of phytoplankton.
[src:shelf-break-front/shelf-break-front] Too much higher, and the stratification of the water column will not cause the upwellings of nutrients needed for the phytoplankton to prosper, too much lower, and the water will be too turbulent for the phytoplankton to use the nutrients available.
[src:shelf-break-front/shelf-break-front] Stability of the front, in addition to nutrients, is a key to phytoplankton production.
[src:shelf-break-front/shelf-break-front] An illustration of the stratification index for Narragansett Bay is shown here, with the average speeds estimated, using actual bathymetry for the bay, and an estimated $C_{D}$ for silt, which composes much of the bay's bottom.
[src:shelf-break-front/shelf-break-front] Using the Stokes Spreadsheet, and some customization on the size of silt particles, I used a $C_{D}$ = 0.0011.
[src:shelf-break-front/shelf-break-front] More accurate speed measurements and detailed $C_{D}$ values for the Bay's bottom could yield a higher fidelity image.
[src:shelf-break-front/shelf-break-front] Notice the green color (a stratification index of approximately 1.5) along the edges of the Northern Bay and near some of the islands.
[src:shelf-break-front/shelf-break-front] These areas are favorable to the formation of algal blooms in the Narraganset Bay habitat due to the stratification index being approximately 1.5.
[src:shelf-break-front/shelf-break-front] Algae have been observed in high concentration in some of these areas, but not all of them.
[src:shelf-break-front/shelf-break-front] Using flow cytometry, results have determined that the relative abundance of picophytoplankton (< 2 $\mu$ m), small nanophytoplankton (2 to 10 $\mu$ m) and large nanophytoplankton (10-20 $\mu$ m) are greatly affected by the stratification index of the water column.
[src:shelf-break-front/shelf-break-front] Cell diversity was greatest in the presence of moderate levels of stratification.
[src:shelf-break-front/shelf-break-front] If the turbulence is too high, their numbers remain stable or fall, but if there is no turbulence, their numbers do fall.
[src:shelf-break-front/shelf-break-front] It is postulated that the nutrient-rich boundary layer around each phytoplankton cell is not exhausted, but renewed, by this moderate level of turbulence.
